,000\n|-\n|align=center|9|| {{flagicon|Georgia (U.S. state)}} Atlanta, GA (Metro Area) || {{flagicon|Florida}} Orlando, FL (Metro Area) || 2,620,000\n|-\n|align=center|10|| {{flagicon|Illinois}} Chicago, IL (Metro Area) || {{flagicon|Washington, D.C.}} Washington, DC (Metro Area) || 2,620,000\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Transport}}\n* [[World's busiest airport]]\n* [[World's busiest airports by traffic movements]]\n* [[World's busiest airports by passenger traffic]]\n*[[Busiest airports in Europe by passenger traffic]]\n*[[List of the largest airports in the Nordic countries]]<sup>1</sup>\n*[[List of the busiest airports in the Baltic states]]<sup>1</sup>\n \n<sup>1</sup> <small>Includes very detailed statistics regarding busiest passenger air routes to/from and within this region</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Aviation statistics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World's Busiest Passenger Air Routes}}\n[[Category:Aviation statistics]]\n[[Category:Aviation-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of superlatives|Busiest Passenger Air Routes]]\n", "name_user": "StefanPlessas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld:Changed 100 to 50 in the title. The list was showing 50 points, but the title said 100.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_busiest_passenger_air_routes"}
{"title_page": "Chanel Miller", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = {{bda|1992|06|12}} \n| birth_place      = [[Palo Alto]], California,<br>United States\n| occupation       = Author\n| language         = English\n| alma_mater       = [[University of California, Santa Barbara|University of California,<br>Santa Barbara]]\n| period           = 2019\n| subject          = [[Memoir]]\n| awards           = ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' Woman of the Year (2016, 2019)\n| website          = {{URL|Chanel-Miller.com}}\n}}\n'''Chanel Miller''' (born June 12, 1992) is an American writer based in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, California]].<ref name=\"PRH Bio\">{{cite web |title=Chanel Miller |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/2211869/chanel-miller |website=Penguin Random House |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> She first came into the public eye anonymously after [[People v. Turner|she was sexually assaulted]] [[Campus sexual assault|on the campus]] of [[Stanford University]] in 2015 by [[People v. Turner|Brock Allen Turner]]. The victim impact statement she wrote and read at her assailant's sentencing hearing the following year went viral after it was published online by ''[[Buzzfeed]]'', and was read 11 million times within four days.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Miller was referred to as [[John Doe|Emily Doe]] in court documents and in media reports until September 2019, when she relinquished her anonymity and published her acclaimed memoir ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]'' which won the 2019 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] (Autobiography).<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Award Winners |url=https://www.bookcritics.org/2020/03/12/2020-awards/ |work=bookcritics.org |author=Beth Parker |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> She is credited with sparking national discussion in the United States about the treatment of sexual assault cases and victims by college campuses and court systems.\n\n==Early life==\nChanel Miller was born in 1992<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|url=|title=Know My Name|last=Miller|first=Chanel|date=2019|publisher=|isbn=|location=|page=10|author-link=}}</ref><ref name=\"Whitaker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chanel-miller-full-60-minutes-interview-know-my-name-author-brock-turner-sexual-assault-survivor-2019-09-22/|title=\"Know My Name\": Author and sexual assault survivor Chanel Miller's full \"60 Minutes\" interview|last=Whitaker|first=Bill|author-link=Bill Whitaker (journalist)|date=September 22, 2019|website=60 Minutes|access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> in [[Palo Alto, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2019/09/23/rape-is-not-a-punishment-for-getting-drunk-chanel-miller-speaks-out-during-her-first-interview-about-being-sexually-assaulted-by-brock-turner|title='Rape is not a punishment for getting drunk.' Chanel Miller speaks out during her first interview about being sexually assaulted by Brock Turner|last=Kadvany|first=Elena|website=www.paloaltoonline.com|language=en|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> Her mother emigrated from China to become a writer and her father is a retired therapist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/brock-turner-sex-assault-woman-chanel-miller-decided-come-forward/| title=Why Brock Turner's Sex Assault Victim Decided to Come Forward| first= Sandra | last=Sobieraj Westfall| first2= Greg | last2=Hanlon|date=September 23, 2019|access-date=October 3, 2019|website=People}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/books/review/chanel-miller-know-my-name.html| title='Know My Name,' a Sexual Assault Survivor Tells the World| first=Jennifer| last=Weiner| date=September 24, 2019| access-date=October 2, 2019|author-link=Jennifer Weiner|website=The New York Times}}</ref> She has a younger sister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/09/review-chanel-millers-incredible-memoir-know-my-name.html| title=Chanel Miller's Story Needed to Be Told in Her Own Words| last=Silman| first=Anna| date=September 23, 2019| access-date=October 2, 2019|website=The Cut}}</ref> She attended the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]]'s [[College of Creative Studies]] where she graduated with a degree in literature in 2014.<ref name=\"Whitaker\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ccs.ucsb.edu/news/2019/ccs-attendee-chanel-miller-announces-forthcoming-memoir-know-my-name| title=CCS Attendee Chanel Miller Announces Forthcoming Memoir, Know My Name| date=September 11, 2019| access-date=October 3, 2019|website=UC Santa Barbara College of Creative Studies}}</ref>\n\n==2015 assault and ''Know My Name''==\n\n{{Main|People v. Turner}}\n\nOn the evening of January 17, 2015, Miller accompanied her sister to a [[Kappa Alpha Order|Kappa Alpha]] fraternity party at [[Stanford University]]; later that night, two Stanford graduate students found Miller lying on the ground behind a dumpster with another Stanford student, 19-year-old Brock Turner, on top of her.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Victor|last=Xu|url=https://www.stanforddaily.com/2016/06/02/brock-turner-sentenced-to-six-months-in-county-jail-three-years-probation/ |title = Brock Turner sentenced to six months in county jail, three years probation|newspaper=[[The Stanford Daily]]|publisher=The Stanford Daily Publishing Corporation|location=Stanford, California|date = June 2, 2016}}</ref> Miller was unconscious, with alcohol in her system.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed 2016\" /> When he tried to flee, Turner was caught and held down on the ground by the other two men as they waited for police to arrive.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Scott|last=Herhold| url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/03/21/herhold-thanking-two-stanford-students-who-subdued-campus-sex-assault-suspect/ | title=Herhold: Thanking two Stanford students who subdued campus sex assault suspect|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|location=San Jose, California| date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> Turner was arrested and indicted on five [[sexual assault]] charges, to which he pleaded not guilty.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Tracey|last=Kaplan| url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/02/02/former-stanford-swimmer-pleads-not-guilty-to-rape-charges/ |title = Former Stanford swimmer pleads not guilty to rape charges|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|location=San Jose, California|date = February 2, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, he was convicted of three of these charges and was sentenced to six months' imprisonment\u2014a sentence which sparked public outrage due to its leniency.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/07/us/outrage-in-stanford-rape-case-over-dueling-statements-of-victim-and-attackers-father.html |title = Light Sentence for Brock Turner in Stanford Rape Case Draws Outrage|newspaper =[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date = June 6, 2016|last1 = Stack|first1 = Liam}}</ref> Sentencing judge [[Aaron Persky]] was [[recall election|recalled]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Bob|last=Egelko| url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Judge-Persky-losing-in-bid-to-avoid-recall-12970799.php | title=Judge Aaron Persky, who ruled in sex assault case, recalled in Santa Clara County|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|location=San Francisco, California| date=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 7,137-word-long victim impact statement by Miller, who was referred to in court documents and media reports as \"[[John Doe|Emily Doe]]\" for the sake of her anonymity, was published by ''[[Buzzfeed]]'' on June 3, 2016, the day after Turner was sentenced,<ref name=\"Buzzfeed 2016\">{{cite web |last1=Baker |first1=Katie J.M. |title=Here's The Powerful Letter The Stanford Victim Read To Her Attacker |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/katiejmbaker/heres-the-powerful-letter-the-stanford-victim-read-to-her-ra |website=[[Buzzfeed]] |publisher=Buzzfeed Media Group|location=New York City|date=June 3, 2016|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> and was reprinted in other major news outlets such as ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT Victim's Statement\">{{cite news |title=Court Statement of Stanford Rape Victim |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/06/08/us/stanford-rape-victim-statement.html?module=inline |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City |accessdate=September 6, 2019|date = June 8, 2016}}</ref> The victim impact statement was read 11 million times in four days after it was published, going viral.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49583310| title=Stanford sexual assault: Chanel Miller reveals her identity| date=4 September 2019| access-date=11 February 2020| website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Miller relinquished her anonymity, being interviewed on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' and publishing a memoir entitled ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]''. The book, published by [[Viking Books]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/22/books/chanel-miller-know-my-name-emily-doe.html|title=\u2018It Will Always Be a Part of My Life\u2019: Chanel Miller Is Ready to Talk|last=de Le\u00f3n|first=Concepci\u00f3n|date=September 22, 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> became a best-seller,<ref name=\"bookpulse\">{{citation|last=Wyatt|first=Neal|title=New Bestsellers, Oct. 3, 2019 - Book Pulse|date=October 3, 2019|url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?detailStory=bestsellers-bookpulse-1032019|work=[[Library Journal]]|publisher=[[Media Source Inc.]]|location=New York City|quote=Know My Name: A Memoir by Chanel Miller (Viking: Penguin) reclaims her story at No. 5 on the NYT Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers list and No. 14 on the USA Today Best-Selling Books list.|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytbestseller\">{{citation|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Oct 13. 2019|date=October 13, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/10/13/hardcover-nonfiction/|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=New This Week - Know My Name - by Chanel Miller - Viking - A sexual assault victim reclaims her identity and challenges our culture and criminal justice system as they relate to this issue.|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"wsjbest\">{{cite news|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended September 28|date=October 3, 2019|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-september-28-11570117918|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|location=New York City|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> was named one of the top ten books of 2019 by the ''[[Washington Post]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/entertainment/books/best-books-of-2019/|title=Best Books of 2019|date=November 21, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> and was nominated for Best Memoir & Autobiography at the 2019 [[Goodreads]] Choice Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/choiceawards/best-memoir-autobiography-books-2019|title=Best Memoir & Autobiography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Goodreads]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' also selected ''Know My Name'' for its \"100 Notable Books of 2019.\" <ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite web |title=100 Notable Books of 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/books/notable-books.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nMiller's story and the legal case \"sparked a nationwide discussion about [[Campus sexual assault|rape on college campuses]] and how survivors were not being heard\"<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/553663/know-my-name-by-chanel-miller/9780735223707/|title=Chanel Miller: Stanford Rape Survivor Wants You to Know Her Name|last1=Cleary|first1=Tom|website=Heavy.|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/23/762028606/chanel-miller-says-know-my-name-as-she-reflects-on-her-assault-by-brock-turner|title=Chanel Miller Says 'Know My Name,' As She Reflects On Her Assault By Brock Turner|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> and \"became part of the intense debates around rape, sexism and sexual misconduct over the past years,\" including the [[Me Too movement]].<ref name=\"NYT Aug 2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/books/chanel-miller-brock-turner-assault-stanford.html|title=You Know Emily Doe's Story. Now Learn Her Name.|last1=de Le\u00f3n|first1=Concepci\u00f3n|date=September 4, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2016, ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' named Miller a woman of the year for \"changing the conversation about sexual assault forever\", citing that her impact statement had been read over 11 million times.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glamour.com/story/women-of-the-year-emily-doe|title=Glamour Women of the Year: Stanford Sexual Assault Case Survivor Emily Doe Speaks Out|website=glamour.com|publisher=Glamour Magazine|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> Miller attended the award ceremony anonymously.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/11/12/once-an-unnamed-sexual-assault-victim-chanel-miller-accepts-woman-year-award-this-time-herself/|title=Once an unnamed sexual assault victim, Chanel Miller accepts Woman of the Year award \u2014 this time, herself|last=Shammas|first=Brittany|date=November 12, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In November 2019, after the publication of her book, Miller attended ''Glamour''<nowiki/>'s award ceremony again, where she was again recognized as a Woman of the Year. She delivered a poem on stage, in which she advocated for the well-being of sexual assault survivors.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was listed as an influential person in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2019 [[Time 100|100]] Next list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/sexual-assault-survivor-chanel-miller-makes-time-magazine-100-next/SiH767UbYUv4sKS3S8V9vO/|title=Chanel Miller on Time magazine's 100 next list|website=www.whio.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]'' (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://chanel-miller.com/}}\n* [https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/katiejmbaker/heres-the-powerful-letter-the-stanford-victim-read-to-her-ra Victim Impact Statement as Published by Buzzfeed] \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Chanel}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American writers of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American victims of crime]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse victim advocates]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women memoirists]]\n", "text_old": "\u2032{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = {{bda|1992|06|12}} \n| birth_place      = [[Palo Alto]], California,<br>United States\n| occupation       = Author\n| language         = English\n| alma_mater       = [[University of California, Santa Barbara|University of California,<br>Santa Barbara]]\n| period           = 2019\n| subject          = [[Memoir]]\n| awards           = ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' Woman of the Year (2016, 2019)\n| website          = {{URL|Chanel-Miller.com}}\n}}\n'''Chanel Miller''' (born June 12, 1992) is an American writer based in [[San Francisco|San Francisco, California]].<ref name=\"PRH Bio\">{{cite web |title=Chanel Miller |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/2211869/chanel-miller |website=Penguin Random House |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> She first came into the public eye anonymously after [[People v. Turner|she was sexually assaulted]] [[Campus sexual assault|on the campus]] of [[Stanford University]] in 2015 by [[People v. Turner|Brock Allen Turner]]. The victim impact statement she wrote and read at her assailant's sentencing hearing the following year went viral after it was published online by ''[[Buzzfeed]]'', and was read 11 million times within four days.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Miller was referred to as [[John Doe|Emily Doe]] in court documents and in media reports until September 2019, when she relinquished her anonymity and published her acclaimed memoir ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]'' which won the 2019 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] (Autobiography).<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Award Winners |url=https://www.bookcritics.org/2020/03/12/2020-awards/ |work=bookcritics.org |author=Beth Parker |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>. She is credited with sparking national discussion in the United States about the treatment of sexual assault cases and victims by college campuses and court systems.\n\n==Early life==\nChanel Miller was born in 1992<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|url=|title=Know My Name|last=Miller|first=Chanel|date=2019|publisher=|isbn=|location=|page=10|author-link=}}</ref><ref name=\"Whitaker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chanel-miller-full-60-minutes-interview-know-my-name-author-brock-turner-sexual-assault-survivor-2019-09-22/|title=\"Know My Name\": Author and sexual assault survivor Chanel Miller's full \"60 Minutes\" interview|last=Whitaker|first=Bill|author-link=Bill Whitaker (journalist)|date=September 22, 2019|website=60 Minutes|access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> in [[Palo Alto, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2019/09/23/rape-is-not-a-punishment-for-getting-drunk-chanel-miller-speaks-out-during-her-first-interview-about-being-sexually-assaulted-by-brock-turner|title='Rape is not a punishment for getting drunk.' Chanel Miller speaks out during her first interview about being sexually assaulted by Brock Turner|last=Kadvany|first=Elena|website=www.paloaltoonline.com|language=en|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> Her mother emigrated from China to become a writer and her father is a retired therapist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/crime/brock-turner-sex-assault-woman-chanel-miller-decided-come-forward/| title=Why Brock Turner's Sex Assault Victim Decided to Come Forward| first= Sandra | last=Sobieraj Westfall| first2= Greg | last2=Hanlon|date=September 23, 2019|access-date=October 3, 2019|website=People}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/books/review/chanel-miller-know-my-name.html| title='Know My Name,' a Sexual Assault Survivor Tells the World| first=Jennifer| last=Weiner| date=September 24, 2019| access-date=October 2, 2019|author-link=Jennifer Weiner|website=The New York Times}}</ref> She has a younger sister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2019/09/review-chanel-millers-incredible-memoir-know-my-name.html| title=Chanel Miller's Story Needed to Be Told in Her Own Words| last=Silman| first=Anna| date=September 23, 2019| access-date=October 2, 2019|website=The Cut}}</ref> She attended the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]]'s [[College of Creative Studies]] where she graduated with a degree in literature in 2014.<ref name=\"Whitaker\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ccs.ucsb.edu/news/2019/ccs-attendee-chanel-miller-announces-forthcoming-memoir-know-my-name| title=CCS Attendee Chanel Miller Announces Forthcoming Memoir, Know My Name| date=September 11, 2019| access-date=October 3, 2019|website=UC Santa Barbara College of Creative Studies}}</ref>\n\n==2015 assault and ''Know My Name''==\n\n{{Main|People v. Turner}}\n\nOn the evening of January 17, 2015, Miller accompanied her sister to a [[Kappa Alpha Order|Kappa Alpha]] fraternity party at [[Stanford University]]; later that night, two Stanford graduate students found Miller lying on the ground behind a dumpster with another Stanford student, 19-year-old Brock Turner, on top of her.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Victor|last=Xu|url=https://www.stanforddaily.com/2016/06/02/brock-turner-sentenced-to-six-months-in-county-jail-three-years-probation/ |title = Brock Turner sentenced to six months in county jail, three years probation|newspaper=[[The Stanford Daily]]|publisher=The Stanford Daily Publishing Corporation|location=Stanford, California|date = June 2, 2016}}</ref> Miller was unconscious, with alcohol in her system.<ref name=\"Buzzfeed 2016\" /> When he tried to flee, Turner was caught and held down on the ground by the other two men as they waited for police to arrive.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Scott|last=Herhold| url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/03/21/herhold-thanking-two-stanford-students-who-subdued-campus-sex-assault-suspect/ | title=Herhold: Thanking two Stanford students who subdued campus sex assault suspect|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|location=San Jose, California| date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> Turner was arrested and indicted on five [[sexual assault]] charges, to which he pleaded not guilty.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Tracey|last=Kaplan| url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/02/02/former-stanford-swimmer-pleads-not-guilty-to-rape-charges/ |title = Former Stanford swimmer pleads not guilty to rape charges|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|location=San Jose, California|date = February 2, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, he was convicted of three of these charges and was sentenced to six months' imprisonment\u2014a sentence which sparked public outrage due to its leniency.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/07/us/outrage-in-stanford-rape-case-over-dueling-statements-of-victim-and-attackers-father.html |title = Light Sentence for Brock Turner in Stanford Rape Case Draws Outrage|newspaper =[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date = June 6, 2016|last1 = Stack|first1 = Liam}}</ref> Sentencing judge [[Aaron Persky]] was [[recall election|recalled]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Bob|last=Egelko| url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Judge-Persky-losing-in-bid-to-avoid-recall-12970799.php | title=Judge Aaron Persky, who ruled in sex assault case, recalled in Santa Clara County|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|location=San Francisco, California| date=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 7,137-word-long victim impact statement by Miller, who was referred to in court documents and media reports as \"[[John Doe|Emily Doe]]\" for the sake of her anonymity, was published by ''[[Buzzfeed]]'' on June 3, 2016, the day after Turner was sentenced,<ref name=\"Buzzfeed 2016\">{{cite web |last1=Baker |first1=Katie J.M. |title=Here's The Powerful Letter The Stanford Victim Read To Her Attacker |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/katiejmbaker/heres-the-powerful-letter-the-stanford-victim-read-to-her-ra |website=[[Buzzfeed]] |publisher=Buzzfeed Media Group|location=New York City|date=June 3, 2016|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> and was reprinted in other major news outlets such as ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT Victim's Statement\">{{cite news |title=Court Statement of Stanford Rape Victim |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/06/08/us/stanford-rape-victim-statement.html?module=inline |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City |accessdate=September 6, 2019|date = June 8, 2016}}</ref> The victim impact statement was read 11 million times in four days after it was published, going viral.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49583310| title=Stanford sexual assault: Chanel Miller reveals her identity| date=4 September 2019| access-date=11 February 2020| website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Miller relinquished her anonymity, being interviewed on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' and publishing a memoir entitled ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]''. The book, published by [[Viking Books]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/22/books/chanel-miller-know-my-name-emily-doe.html|title=\u2018It Will Always Be a Part of My Life\u2019: Chanel Miller Is Ready to Talk|last=de Le\u00f3n|first=Concepci\u00f3n|date=September 22, 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> became a best-seller,<ref name=\"bookpulse\">{{citation|last=Wyatt|first=Neal|title=New Bestsellers, Oct. 3, 2019 - Book Pulse|date=October 3, 2019|url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?detailStory=bestsellers-bookpulse-1032019|work=[[Library Journal]]|publisher=[[Media Source Inc.]]|location=New York City|quote=Know My Name: A Memoir by Chanel Miller (Viking: Penguin) reclaims her story at No. 5 on the NYT Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers list and No. 14 on the USA Today Best-Selling Books list.|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytbestseller\">{{citation|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Oct 13. 2019|date=October 13, 2019|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/10/13/hardcover-nonfiction/|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=New This Week - Know My Name - by Chanel Miller - Viking - A sexual assault victim reclaims her identity and challenges our culture and criminal justice system as they relate to this issue.|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"wsjbest\">{{cite news|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended September 28|date=October 3, 2019|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-september-28-11570117918|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|location=New York City|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> was named one of the top ten books of 2019 by the ''[[Washington Post]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/entertainment/books/best-books-of-2019/|title=Best Books of 2019|date=November 21, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> and was nominated for Best Memoir & Autobiography at the 2019 [[Goodreads]] Choice Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/choiceawards/best-memoir-autobiography-books-2019|title=Best Memoir & Autobiography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Goodreads]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' also selected ''Know My Name'' for its \"100 Notable Books of 2019.\" <ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite web |title=100 Notable Books of 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/books/notable-books.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nMiller's story and the legal case \"sparked a nationwide discussion about [[Campus sexual assault|rape on college campuses]] and how survivors were not being heard\"<ref name=\"Heavy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/553663/know-my-name-by-chanel-miller/9780735223707/|title=Chanel Miller: Stanford Rape Survivor Wants You to Know Her Name|last1=Cleary|first1=Tom|website=Heavy.|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/23/762028606/chanel-miller-says-know-my-name-as-she-reflects-on-her-assault-by-brock-turner|title=Chanel Miller Says 'Know My Name,' As She Reflects On Her Assault By Brock Turner|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> and \"became part of the intense debates around rape, sexism and sexual misconduct over the past years,\" including the [[Me Too movement]].<ref name=\"NYT Aug 2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/books/chanel-miller-brock-turner-assault-stanford.html|title=You Know Emily Doe's Story. Now Learn Her Name.|last1=de Le\u00f3n|first1=Concepci\u00f3n|date=September 4, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2016, ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' named Miller a woman of the year for \"changing the conversation about sexual assault forever\", citing that her impact statement had been read over 11 million times.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glamour.com/story/women-of-the-year-emily-doe|title=Glamour Women of the Year: Stanford Sexual Assault Case Survivor Emily Doe Speaks Out|website=glamour.com|publisher=Glamour Magazine|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> Miller attended the award ceremony anonymously.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/11/12/once-an-unnamed-sexual-assault-victim-chanel-miller-accepts-woman-year-award-this-time-herself/|title=Once an unnamed sexual assault victim, Chanel Miller accepts Woman of the Year award \u2014 this time, herself|last=Shammas|first=Brittany|date=November 12, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In November 2019, after the publication of her book, Miller attended ''Glamour''<nowiki/>'s award ceremony again, where she was again recognized as a Woman of the Year. She delivered a poem on stage, in which she advocated for the well-being of sexual assault survivors.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was listed as an influential person in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2019 [[Time 100|100]] Next list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whio.com/news/local/sexual-assault-survivor-chanel-miller-makes-time-magazine-100-next/SiH767UbYUv4sKS3S8V9vO/|title=Chanel Miller on Time magazine's 100 next list|website=www.whio.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''[[Know My Name (book)|Know My Name]]'' (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://chanel-miller.com/}}\n* [https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/katiejmbaker/heres-the-powerful-letter-the-stanford-victim-read-to-her-ra Victim Impact Statement as Published by Buzzfeed] \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Chanel}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American writers of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American victims of crime]]\n[[Category:Sexual abuse victim advocates]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American women memoirists]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chanel_Miller"}
{"title_page": "School for Scoundrels (1960 film)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = School for Scoundrels\n| image          = School_for_Scoundrels_1960_UK_poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original UK poster\n| director       = [[Robert Hamer]]<br />[[Cyril Frankel]] (uncredited),<br />[[Hal E. Chester]] (uncredited)<ref name = \"Brooke\">{{cite web|last=Brooke|first=Michael|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/487382/|title=School for Scoundrels (1959)|work=BFI Screenonline|date=2003\u201314|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n| producer       = Hal E. Chester\n| screenplay         = Hal E. Chester<br />[[Patricia Moyes]]<br />[[Peter Ustinov]] {{small|(uncredited)}}<br />[[Frank Tarloff]] {{small|(uncredited)}}\n| based on       = {{based on|the ''[[Gamesmanship]]'' series|[[Stephen Potter]]}}\n| starring       = [[Ian Carmichael]]<br/>[[Terry-Thomas]]<br />[[Janette Scott]]<br />[[Alastair Sim]]\n| music          = [[John Addison]]\n| cinematography = [[Erwin Hillier]]\n| editing        = [[Richard Best (film editor)|Richard Best]]\n| studio = [[Associated British Picture Corporation]] (ABPC)<br />Guardsman Films<ref name=\"Brooke\" />\n| distributor    = <!-- Link as for ABPC. -->Warner-Path\u00e9 Distributors<ref name=BBFC /> {{small|(UK)}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|1960|03|24|UK}}<ref name=Times1960>''The Times'', 24 March 1960, p. 2 (advert) and p. 12 (review)</ref>\n| runtime        = 97 minutes<ref name=BBFC>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/school-scoundrels-1970-4|title=''School for Scoundrels''|work= BBFC|access-date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''School for Scoundrels''''' is a 1960 British [[comedy film]] directed by [[Robert Hamer]] (and an uncredited [[Cyril Frankel]] and Hal Chester).<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> It stars [[Ian Carmichael]] and [[Terry-Thomas]]. It was inspired by the \"[[Gamesmanship]]\" series of books by [[Stephen Potter]]. It has been remade twice: in [[Bollywood]] under the title ''[[Chhoti Si Baat]]'' (1975), and in Hollywood as ''[[School for Scoundrels (2006 film)|School for Scoundrels]]'' (2006).\n\n==Plot==\nHenry Palfrey ([[Ian Carmichael]]) is a failure in sport and love, and the easy victim of [[confidence trick|conmen]] and employees alike. So he enrols at the \"School of Lifemanship\" in [[Yeovil]], run by Dr. Potter ([[Alastair Sim]]). Late for his appointment, he overhears Potter explaining the principles of [[gamesmanship|lifemanship]] to the new intake: {{quote|Well, gentlemen, lifemanship is the science of being one up on your opponents at all times. It is the art of making him feel that somewhere, somehow he has become less than you \u2013 less desirable, less worthy \u2013 less blessed.<ref name = sim/>}} Palfrey is given an object lesson in this when he has his interview with Potter, who proceeds to win a name-calling game. When Palfrey explains that he is a failure, Potter surmises that a woman is involved. In [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]], Palfrey recounts how he first met April Smith ([[Janette Scott]]), knocking parcels from her hands when he rushes to catch a bus. He manages to arrange a dinner date with her.\n\nWhen Palfrey shows up at work, his loafing employees are unconcerned, despite his being the head of the family firm. They pay much more respect to his senior clerk, Gloatbridge ([[Edward Chapman (actor)|Edward Chapman]]). In private, Gloatbridge is patronising toward his erstwhile boss, making the business decisions. Palfrey asks him to make a dinner reservation, and has to fend off Gloatbridge's unwanted restaurant suggestion. \n\nThat night at the restaurant, the head waiter ([[John Le Mesurier]]) cannot find Palfrey's booking at first; he does finally locate it under a slightly different name, but still refuses to seat them, as they are late. When Raymond Delauney ([[Terry-Thomas]]), a casual acquaintance of Palfrey's, arrives and sees April, he invites them to his table, where he proceeds to try to seduce April and cast Palfrey in a bad light at every opportunity.\n\nAs Delauney has a fancy sports car, Palfrey tries to counter by purchasing an automobile of his own. However, two salesmen ([[Dennis Price]] and [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]]) sell him a ramshackle 1924 \"Swiftmobile\". To further his humiliation of his rival, Delauney suggests a \"friendly\" [[tennis]] match; he wins easily. The film then returns to the school. Over the next several weeks, Palfrey proves to be an apt pupil in learning various ploys to gain the upper hand. The next phase of his education involves a field test of his new skills, evaluated by Potter. Palfrey convinces the car salesmen that his car, after some tune-up, is now a valuable and sought-after vehicle. They trade him a sports car and 100 guineas (\u00a3105) for his Swiftmobile, which promptly breaks down.\n\nAfter putting Gloatbridge in his place, Palfrey challenges Delauney to a rematch. Using some stratagems, he thoroughly frustrates his foe before they even start playing. Then, with April watching, Palfrey proceeds to win the set 6-0. April becomes disgusted with Delauney's behaviour afterward and drives off with Palfrey. They go back to his place for a drink. \n\nPalfrey arranges for April's scotch and soda to spill on her dress. He suggests she take it off to dry and put on his dressing gown. Eventually, they end up in his bedroom through his tricks, but Palfrey cannot bring himself to take advantage of April. Then Delauney barges in, dragging Potter with him. Delauney had found out that Potter was Palfrey's guest at the tennis club and got the story out of him. However, after Delauney informs her, April realises that Palfrey genuinely loves her, and they embrace, much to the disgust of both Delauney and Potter. Potter breaks the \"[[fourth wall]]\" and apologises to the audience for his pupil's behaviour.\n\nThe film ends with Delauney getting off the train at [[Yeovil]] station and heading in the direction of the school.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Ian Carmichael]] as Henry Palfrey\n* [[Terry-Thomas]] as Raymond Delauney\n* [[Alastair Sim]] as Mr. S. Potter\n* [[Janette Scott]] as April Smith\n* [[Dennis Price]] as Dunstan Dorchester\n* [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] as Dudley Dorchester\n* [[Edward Chapman (actor)|Edward Chapman]] as Gloatbridge\n* [[John Le Mesurier]] as Head Waiter\n* [[Irene Handl]] as Mrs. Stringer, Palfrey's landlady\n* [[Kynaston Reeves]] as General\n* [[Hattie Jacques]] as 1st Instructress\n* [[Hugh Paddick]] as Instructor\n* Barbara Roscoe as 2nd Instructress\n* [[Gerald Campion]] as Proudfoot, a school student\n* [[Monte Landis]] as Fleetsnod, a school student\n* [[Jeremy Lloyd]] as Dingle, a school student\n* [[Charles Lamb (actor)|Charles Lamb]] as Carpenter\n* [[Anita Sharp-Bolster]] as Maid\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nStephen Potter's original ''[[Gamesmanship]]'' had been a successful series of books in the 1950s, but were not written in a narrative form,<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> so the device was adopted that Potter ([[Alastair Sim]]) had set up a \"College of Lifemanship\" in [[Yeovil]] to educate those seeking to apply his methods for success.<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Some interest had previously been shown by [[Cary Grant]] (with [[Carl Foreman]]) in a filmed version of Potter's books, but this failed when no way could be found of translating the dry humour for an American audience.<ref name= sim>{{cite web |url=http://www.alastairsim.net/Film/schoolforscoundrels.htm |title=School for Scoundrels |publisher=alastairsim.net |accessdate=2010-11-01 }}</ref> The film's title is a reference to [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s 1777 comic play, ''[[The School for Scandal]]''.<ref name = sim/>\n\nAlthough the film only credits its producer, [[Hal E. Chester]], and [[Patricia Moyes]] for the screenplay, it was co-written by [[Peter Ustinov]] and [[Frank Tarloff]].<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Its director, [[Robert Hamer]], was sacked during filming due to his return to [[alcoholism|drinking]] and the enterprise was completed by Chester and an (uncredited) [[Cyril Frankel]].<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Hamer did not work in the film industry again, and died in 1963.<ref name = \"Brooke\" />\n\nThe dishonest car salesmen calling themselves the \"Winsome Welshmen\", Dunstan ([[Dennis Price]]) and Dudley ([[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]]), were based on similar characters in a 1950s BBC radio comedy series, ''In All Directions'', in which the leads were played by [[Peter Ustinov]] and Jones; their catch phrase \"run for it!\" was recycled in ''School for Scoundrels''.<ref name= sim/>\n\n''School for Scoundrels'' was made at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]], and location scenes were mainly shot in the vicinity.<ref name = locations>{{cite web |url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/s/schoolscoundrels.html |title=Film locations for School for Scoundrels (1960) |publisher=www.movie-locations.com |accessdate=2010-11-01 }}</ref> The location used as the tennis club was then a private members club before its current incarnation as a hotel. The hotel hosted a screening in 2016 with Janette Scott attending and answering questions about filming ''School For Scoundrels''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://artandhue.com/happy-birthday-janette-scott/|title=Happy Birthday Janette Scott! - Stylish Pop Art - Bespoke & Custom Art|date=2016-12-14|newspaper=Art & Hue|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-04}}</ref>\n\nThe film uses vehicles as plot devices. Palfrey foolishly buys a \"1924 4-litre Swiftmobile\" from the crooked \"Winsome Welshmen\". Later in the film he succeeds in trading the car back to them for an ex-works [[Austin-Healey 100#100-Six .28BN4 and BN6.29|Austin-Healey 100-six]] and \u00a3100. The \"Swiftmobile\" was in fact based upon a [[Bentley 4\u00bd Litre|1928 4\u00bd litre Open four-seater Bentley]], with a custom two-seat open body. The car, minus the body, was sold by the studio in 1961 for \u00a350, and re-sold (with new body) at an auction in 2003 for \u00a3110,000. The Austin-Healey 100-six used in the film was passed in at auction in the 1970s at around \u00a330,000. The \"Bellini 3.6\" driven by Terry-Thomas is in fact a disguised [[Aston Martin DB3S]].<ref name = swift>{{cite web |url=http://www.swiftmobile.com/  |title=The Original Swiftmobile |publisher=web.archive.org |accessdate=2010-11-01 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080622224931/http://www.swiftmobile.com/ |archivedate = 22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAfter passing the British censors on 14 December 1959<ref name=BBFC/> ''School for Scoundrels'' premiered at the [[Vue West End|Warner Theatre]] in [[Leicester Square]], London on 24 March 1960.<ref name=Times1960 /> When the film was released in the United States on 11 July 1960, it was given the subtitle \"''or How to Win Without Actually Cheating!''\", reflected in the US poster by [[Tom Jung]].\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was the 12th most popular film at the UK box office in 1960.\n\nWhile the review in ''[[The Times]]'' was very noncommittal,<ref name=Times1960 /> [[Leslie Halliwell]] described the film as \"an amusing trifle, basically a series of sketches by familiar comic actors\", and awarded it one star (of a maximum of four and a minimum of zero).<ref>{{cite book |title = Halliwell's Film & Video Guide|last = Halliwell| first = Leslie| authorlink = Leslie Halliwell | year = 1996|publisher = Harper-Collins| location = London|isbn = 0-00-638779-9| page = 657}}</ref>\n\nMichael Brooke, reviewing for the [[British Film Institute]] many years afterwards, criticised the film as having \"little sign of the elegance and wit that characterised earlier Hamer films such as ''[[Kind Hearts and Coronets]]'' or [[The Spider and the Fly (1949 film)|''The Spider and the Fly'']]\", but praised its script and performances, particularly those of Terry-Thomas and an under-used Sim.<ref name = \"Brooke\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Screenonline title|487382}} \n* {{IMDb title|0054279}}\n\n{{Robert Hamer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School For Scoundrels}}\n[[Category:1960 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1960 comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:Films about con artists]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Hamer]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Addison]]\n[[Category:Films set in schools]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Somerset]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = School for Scoundrels\n| image          = School_for_Scoundrels_1960_UK_poster.jpg\n| caption        = Original UK poster\n| director       = [[Robert Hamer]]<br />[[Cyril Frankel]] (uncredited),<br />[[Hal E. Chester]] (uncredited)<ref name = \"Brooke\">{{cite web|last=Brooke|first=Michael|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/487382/|title=School for Scoundrels (1959)|work=BFI Screenonline|date=2003\u201314|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n| producer       = Hal E. Chester\n| screenplay         = Hal E. Chester<br />[[Patricia Moyes]]<br />[[Peter Ustinov]] {{small|(uncredited)}}<br />[[Frank Tarloff]] {{small|(uncredited)}}\n| based on       = {{based on|the ''[[Gamesmanship]]'' series|[[Stephen Potter]]}}\n| starring       = [[Ian Carmichael]]<br/>[[Terry-Thomas]]<br />[[Janette Scott]]<br />[[Alastair Sim]]\n| music          = [[John Addison]]\n| cinematography = [[Erwin Hillier]]\n| editing        = [[Richard Best (film editor)|Richard Best]]\n| studio = [[Associated British Picture Corporation]] (ABPC)<br />Guardsman Films<ref name=\"Brooke\" />\n| distributor    = <!-- Link as for ABPC. -->Warner-Path\u00e9 Distributors<ref name=BBFC /> {{small|(UK)}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|1960|03|24|UK}}<ref name=Times1960>''The Times'', 24 March 1960, p. 2 (advert) and p. 12 (review)</ref>\n| runtime        = 97 minutes<ref name=BBFC>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/school-scoundrels-1970-4|title=''School for Scoundrels''|work= BBFC|access-date=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''School for Scoundrels''''' is a 1960 British [[comedy film]] directed by [[Robert Hamer]] (and an uncredited [[Cyril Frankel]] and Hal Chester).<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> It stars [[Ian Carmichael]] and [[Terry-Thomas]]. It was inspired by the \"[[Gamesmanship]]\" series of books by [[Stephen Potter]]. It has been remade twice: in [[Bollywood]] under the title ''[[Chhoti Si Baat]]'' (1975), and in Hollywood as ''[[School for Scoundrels (2006 film)|School for Scoundrels]]'' (2006).\n\n==Plot==\nHenry Palfrey ([[Ian Carmichael]]) is a failure in sport and love, and the easy victim of [[confidence trick|conmen]] and employees alike. So he enrols at the \"School of Lifemanship\" in [[Yeovil]], run by Dr. Potter ([[Alastair Sim]]). Late for his appointment, he overhears Potter explaining the principles of [[gamesmanship|lifemanship]] to the new intake: {{quote|Well, gentlemen, lifemanship is the science of being one up on your opponents at all times. It is the art of making him feel that somewhere, somehow he has become less than you \u2013 less desirable, less worthy \u2013 less blessed.<ref name = sim/>}} Palfrey is given an object lesson in this when he has his interview with Potter, who proceeds to win a name-calling game. When Palfrey explains that he is a failure, Potter surmises that a woman is involved. In [[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]], Palfrey recounts how he first met April Smith ([[Janette Scott]]), knocking parcels from her hands when he rushes to catch a bus. He manages to arrange a dinner date with her.\n\nWhen Palfrey shows up at work, his loafing employees are unconcerned, despite his being the head of the family firm. They pay much more respect to his senior clerk, Gloatbridge ([[Edward Chapman (actor)|Edward Chapman]]). In private, Gloatbridge is patronising toward his erstwhile boss, making the business decisions. Palfrey asks him to make a dinner reservation, and has to fend off Gloatbridge's unwanted restaurant suggestion. \n\nThat night at the restaurant, the head waiter ([[John Le Mesurier]]) cannot find Palfrey's booking at first; he does finally locate it under a slightly different name, but still refuses to seat them, as they are late. When Raymond Delauney ([[Terry-Thomas]]), a casual acquaintance of Palfrey's, arrives and sees April, he invites them to his table, where he proceeds to try to seduce April and cast Palfrey in a bad light at every opportunity.\n\nAs Delauney has a fancy sports car, Palfrey tries to counter by purchasing an automobile of his own. However, two salesmen ([[Dennis Price]] and [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]]) sell him a ramshackle 1924 \"Swiftmobile\". To further his humiliation of his rival, Delauney suggests a \"friendly\" [[tennis]] match; he wins easily. The film then returns to the school. Over the next several weeks, Palfrey proves to be an apt pupil in learning various ploys to gain the upper hand. The next phase of his education involves a field test of his new skills, evaluated by Potter. Palfrey convinces the car salesmen that his car, after some tune-up, is now a valuable and sought-after vehicle. They trade him a sports car and 100 guineas (\u00a3105) for his Swiftmobile, which promptly breaks down.\n\nAfter putting Gloatbridge in his place, Palfrey challenges Delauney to a rematch. Using some stratagems, he thoroughly frustrates his foe before they even start playing. Then, with April watching, Palfrey proceeds to win the set 6-0. April becomes disgusted with Delauney's behaviour afterward and drives off with Palfrey. They go back to his place for a drink. \n\nPalfrey arranges for April's scotch and soda to spill on her dress. He suggests she take it off to dry and put on his dressing gown. Eventually, they end up in his bedroom through his tricks, but Palfrey cannot bring himself to take advantage of April. Then Delauney barges in, dragging Potter with him. Delauney had found out that Potter was Palfrey's guest at the tennis club and got the story out of him. However, after Delauney informs her, April realises that Palfrey genuinely loves her, and they embrace, much to the disgust of both Delauney and Potter. Potter breaks the \"[[fourth wall]]\" and apologises to the audience for his pupil's behaviour.\n\nThe film ends with Delauney getting off the train at [[Yeovil]] station and heading in the direction of the school.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Ian Carmichael]] as Henry Palfrey\n* [[Terry-Thomas]] as Raymond Delauney\n* [[Alastair Sim]] as Mr. S. Potter\n* [[Janette Scott]] as April Smith\n* [[Dennis Price]] as Dunstan Dorchester\n* [[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]] as Dudley Dorchester\n* [[Edward Chapman (actor)|Edward Chapman]] as Gloatbridge\n* [[John Le Mesurier]] as Head Waiter\n* [[Irene Handl]] as Mrs. Stringer, Palfrey's landlady\n* [[Kynaston Reeves]] as General\n* [[Hattie Jacques]] as 1st Instructress\n* [[Hugh Paddick]] as Instructor\n* Barbara Roscoe as 2nd Instructress\n* [[Gerald Campion]] as Proudfoot, a school student\n* [[Monte Landis]] as Fleetsnod, a school student\n* [[Jeremy Lloyd]] as Dingle, a school student\n* [[Charles Lamb (actor)|Charles Lamb]] as Carpenter\n* [[Anita Sharp-Bolster]] as Maid\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nStephen Potter's original ''[[Gamesmanship]]'' had been a successful series of books in the 1950s, but were not written in a narrative form,<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> so the device was adopted that Potter ([[Alastair Sim]]) had set up a \"College of Lifemanship\" in [[Yeovil]] to educate those seeking to apply his methods for success.<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Some interest had previously been shown by [[Cary Grant]] (with [[Carl Foreman]]) in a filmed version of Potter's books, but this failed when no way could be found of translating the dry humour for an American audience.<ref name= sim>{{cite web |url=http://www.alastairsim.net/Film/schoolforscoundrels.htm |title=School for Scoundrels |publisher=alastairsim.net |accessdate=2010-11-01 }}</ref> The film's title is a reference to [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]]'s 1777 comic play, ''[[The School for Scandal]]''.<ref name = sim/>\n\nAlthough the film only credits its producer, [[Hal E. Chester]], and [[Patricia Moyes]] for the screenplay, it was co-written by [[Peter Ustinov]] and [[Frank Tarloff]].<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Its director, [[Robert Hamer]], was sacked during filming due to his return to [[alcoholism|drinking]] and the enterprise was completed by Chester and an (uncredited) [[Cyril Frankel]].<ref name = \"Brooke\" /> Hamer did not work in the film industry again, and died in 1963.<ref name = \"Brooke\" />\n\nThe dishonest car salesmen calling themselves the \"Winsome Welshmen\", Dunstan ([[Dennis Price]]) and Dudley ([[Peter Jones (actor)|Peter Jones]]), were based on similar characters in a 1950s BBC radio comedy series, ''In All Directions'', in which the leads were played by [[Peter Ustinov]] and Jones; their catch phrase \"run for it!\" was recycled in ''School for Scoundrels''.<ref name= sim/>\n\n''School for Scoundrels'' was made at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]], and location scenes were mainly shot in the vicinity.<ref name = locations>{{cite web |url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/s/schoolscoundrels.html |title=Film locations for School for Scoundrels (1960) |publisher=www.movie-locations.com |accessdate=2010-11-01 }}</ref> The location used as the tennis club was then a private members club before its current incarnation as a hotel. The hotel hosted a screening in 2016 with Janette Scott attending and answering questions about filming ''School For Scoundrels''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://artandhue.com/happy-birthday-janette-scott/|title=Happy Birthday Janette Scott! - Stylish Pop Art - Bespoke & Custom Art|date=2016-12-14|newspaper=Art & Hue|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-04}}</ref>\n\nThe film uses vehicles as plot devices. Palfrey foolishly buys a \"1924 4-litre Swiftmobile\" from the crooked \"Winsome Welshmen\". Later in the film he succeeds in trading the car back to them for an ex-works [[Austin-Healey 100#100-Six .28BN4 and BN6.29|Austin-Healey 100-six]] and \u00a3100. The \"Swiftmobile\" was in fact based upon a [[Bentley 4\u00bd Litre|1928 4\u00bd litre Open four-seater Bentley]], with a custom two-seat open body. The car, minus the body, was sold by the studio in 1961 for \u00a350, and re-sold (with new body) at an auction in 2003 for \u00a3110,000. The Austin-Healey 100-six used in the film was passed in at auction in the 1970s at around \u00a330,000. The \"Bellini 3.6\" driven by Terry-Thomas is in fact a disguised [[Aston Martin DB3S]].<ref name = swift>{{cite web |url=http://www.swiftmobile.com/  |title=The Original Swiftmobile |publisher=web.archive.org |accessdate=2010-11-01 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080622224931/http://www.swiftmobile.com/ |archivedate = 22 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nAfter passing the British censors on 14 December 1959<ref name=BBFC/> ''School for Scoundrels'' premiered at the [[Vue West End|Warner Theatre]] in [[Leicester Square]], London on 24 March 1960.<ref name=Times1960 /> When the film was released in the United States on 11 July 1960, it was given the subtitle \"''or How to Win Without Actually Cheating!''\", reflected in the US poster by [[Tom Jung]].\n\n==Reception==\nThe film was the 12th most popular film at the UK box office in 1960.\n\nWhile the review in ''[[The Times]]'' was very noncommittal,<ref name=Times1960 /> [[Leslie Halliwell]] described the film as \"an amusing trifle, basically a series of sketches by familiar comic actors\", and awarded it one star (of a maximum of four and a minimum of zero).<ref>{{cite book |title = Halliwell's Film & Video Guide|last = Halliwell| first = Leslie| authorlink = Leslie Halliwell | year = 1996|publisher = Harper-Collins| location = London|isbn = 0-00-638779-9| page = 657}}</ref>\n\nMichael Brooke, reviewing for the [[British Film Institute]] many years afterwards, criticised the film as having \"little sign of the elegance and wit that characterised earlier Hamer films such as ''[[Kind Hearts and Coronets]]'' or [[The Spider and the Fly (1949 film)|''The Spider and the Fly'']]\", but praised its script and performances, particularly those of Terry-Thomas and an under-used Sim.<ref name = \"Brooke\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Screenonline title|487382}} \n* {{IMDb title|0054279}}\n\n{{Robert Hamer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School For Scoundrels}}\n[[Category:1960 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1960s comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Elstree Studios]]\n[[Category:Films about con artists]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Hamer]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Addison]]\n[[Category:Films set in schools]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Somerset]]\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1960s comedy filmstoCategory:1960 comedy filmsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/School_for_Scoundrels_(1960_film)"}
{"title_page": "\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name           = \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya\n| image          = Mehmet \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya.jpg\n| office         = [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start     = October 25, 1937\n| term_end       = November 11, 1938\n| primeminister  = [[Celal Bayar]]\n| successor      = [[Refik Saydam]]\n| office2        = [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start2    = November 1, 1927\n| term_end2      = October 25, 1937\n| primeminister2 = [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| predecessor2   = [[Mehmet Cemil Uybad\u0131n]]\n| office3        = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start3    = November 21, 1924\n| term_end3      = March 3, 1925\n| primeminister3 = [[Ali Fethi Okyar]]\n| predecessor3   = [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| successor3     = [[Tevfik R\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc Aras]]\n| office4        = [[Ministry of Agriculture and Village Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| term_start4    = August 31, 1924\n| term_end4      = October 21, 1924\n| primeminister4 = [[Ismet In\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| predecessor4   = [[Zekai Apayd\u0131n]]\n| successor4     = [[Hasan Fehmi (Ata\u00e7)]]\n| office5        = Mayor and Governor of Izmir\n| term_start5    = 1922\n| term_end5      = 1924\n| birth_date     = 1883\n| birth_place    = [[Kos|Istank\u00f6y]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date     = {{death date|1959|01|10}}\n| death_place    = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| nationality    = Turkish\n| profession     = Jurist\n| spouse         =\n| alma_mater     = [[Galatasaray High School]], [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Law, [[University of Paris]]\n| religion       =\n| party          =\n| signature      = \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya imzas\u0131.png\n| signature_alt  =\n| website        =\n}}\n\n'''\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya''' (1883 &ndash; January 10, 1959) was a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] civil servant and politician, who served as government minister, Minister of Interior  and [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Turkey|Minister of Foreign affairs]] in several governments. \n\n== Biography == \n[[File:\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya Bey.jpg|thumb|150px|left|\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya in the 1920s]]\nBorn in [[\u0130stank\u00f6y]] (Kos), part of [[the Dodecanese]] in the then [[Ottoman Empire]], he finished [[Galatasaray High School]] before he graduated from Law School in 1908. He did his graduate work in [[Paris]], [[France]]. He worked as inspector of treasury for the Empire.\n\nAt the start of [[World War I]], \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc was appointed the Director of Settlement of Tribes and Migrants. The Director of Settlement of Tribes and Migrants was mainly tasked with managing the Armenian deportations during the [[Armenian Genocide]]. In September 1915, he was transferred to [[Aleppo]], an important location along the deportation route into the Syrian desert.<ref name=dundar>{{cite book|last1=D\u00fcndar|first1=Fuat|title=Crime of numbers the role of statistics in the Armenian question (1878-1918)|date=2010|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, NJ|isbn=1412843413|pages=113\u20134|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JwUZ2HeAn8UC}}</ref>\n\nAs the Armenian Genocide was underway, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc was tasked to administrate the concentration camps of Armenian deportees located in Syria. In order to manage the large influx of Armenians into the area, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc started a policy that enforced a certain ratio of Armenians to be left untouched. However, once the Armenians exceeded this ratio, they were evacuated from their camps and subsequently massacred.<ref name=agos>{{cite news|last1=Polatel|first1=Mehmet|title=Social engineer: \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya|url=http://www.agos.com.tr/en/article/11045/social-engineer-sukru-kaya|agency=Agos|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> On 19 December 1915, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc is noted to have said to German engineer Bastendorff the following:<ref name=agos />\n{{quote|The final solution is the termination of the Armenian race. Clashes that have continued between Armenians and Muslims all along have now reached their final stage. The weaker side will be destroyed.}}\n\nHe was then assigned to [[Iraq]] but he resigned and moved to [[\u0130zmir]] (also known as [[Smyrna]]).\n\nHe worked as a teacher in [[Buca]] Sultanisi (high school). After the [[Armistice of Mudros]], he worked for the [[Turkish national movement]]. Following the occupation of Istanbul by The Entente powers, he was arrested by the British administration and was exiled to [[British Malta|Malta]]. He escaped to the continent from Malta and subsequently went to [[Anatolia]] and joined the [[Turkish War of Independence]].\n\nIn September 1925 he was a member of the Reform Conucil for the Reform of the East ({{Lang-tr|\u015eark \u0130slahat Enc\u00fcmeni}})<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dcng\u00f6r|first=U\u011fur \u00dcmit|date=2008-09-23|title=Geographies of Nationalism and Violence: Rethinking Young Turk \u2018Social Engineering\u2019|url=http://journals.openedition.org/ejts/2583|journal=European Journal of Turkish Studies. Social Sciences on Contemporary Turkey|language=en|issue=7|doi=10.4000/ejts.2583|issn=1773-0546}}</ref> which prepared the [[1925 Report for Reform in the East (Turkey)|Report for Reform in the East]] ({{Lang-tr|\u015eark \u0130slahat Raporu}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Goner|first=Ozlem|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=bv8nDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=sark+islahat+raporu+and+the+kurds+s%C3%BCkr%C3%BC+kaya&source=bl&ots=blWLemDPcN&sig=ACfU3U0np4xb_bdqhJ4a_zjAVksFrrfNJQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwix-rvWhPPoAhXIjKQKHT9OANIQ6AEwAXoECAsQMg#v=onepage&q=sark%20islahat%20raporu%20and%20the%20kurds%20s%C3%BCkr%C3%BC%20kaya&f=false|title=Turkish National Identity and Its Outsiders: Memories of State Violence in Dersim|date=14 June 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=|isbn=978-1-315-46296-7|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gunter|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=XjZ7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT195&lpg=PT195&dq=sark+islahat+raporu&source=bl&ots=yUOtVBARTq&sig=ACfU3U3HvofM8NM5rI_HeayKaaaKu6dGFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjXgMOpifPoAhVTycQBHR30DUEQ6AEwB3oECAsQNA#v=onepage&q=sark%20islahat%20raporu&f=false|title=Routledge Handbook on the Kurds|date=2018-08-06|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-23798-3|language=en}}</ref> In 1930 he was the author of the outlines of [[Turkification]] ({{Lang-tr|T\u00fcrkle\u015ftirme Genelgesi}}). Non-Turkish languages should be suppressed and non-Turkish names of locations changed to Turkish ones.<ref name=\":0\" />   \n\n\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya served as Minister of Agriculture, Minister of Foreign Affairs and Interior Minister in several cabinets between 1924 and 1938.\n\nHe died on 10 January 1959, in [[Istanbul]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Who is who database - [http://www.kimkimdir.gen.tr/kimkimdir.php?id=624 ''Biography of \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya''] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |\n   title=[[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Turkey|Minister of Foreign Affairs of Turkey]] |\n   before=[[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]] |\n   years=November 21, 1924&ndash;March 4, 1925 |\n   after= [[Tevfik R\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc Aras]]\n}}\n{{succession box |\n  before=[[Mehmet Cemil Uybad\u0131n]] |\n  title=[[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior of Turkey]] |\n  years=November 1, 1927&ndash;November 11, 1938 |\n  after=[[Refik Saydam]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Turkey}}\n{{Ministers of the Interior of Turkey}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaya, Sukru}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:Galatasaray High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Turkish writers]]\n[[Category:Turkish columnists]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Turkey]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:Malta exiles]]\n[[Category:Civil servants of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Interior of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Turkish civil servants]]\n[[Category:Istanbul University Faculty of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Turkish educators]]\n[[Category:Mayors of \u0130zmir]]\n[[Category:People of the Dersim rebellion]]\n[[Category:Armenian Genocide perpetrators]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 3rd government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th government of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd Parliament of Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name           = \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya\n| image          = Mehmet \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya.jpg\n| office         = [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start     = October 25, 1937\n| term_end       = November 11, 1938\n| primeminister  = [[Celal Bayar]]\n| successor      = [[Refik Saydam]]\n| office2        = [[Ministry of the Interior (Turkey)|Minister of Interior]]\n| term_start2    = November 1, 1927\n| term_end2      = October 25, 1937\n| primeminister2 = [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| predecessor2   = [[Mehmet Cemil Uybad\u0131n]]\n| office3        = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start3    = November 21, 1924\n| term_end3      = March 3, 1925\n| primeminister3 = [[Ali Fethi Okyar]]\n| predecessor3   = [[\u0130smet \u0130n\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| successor3     = [[Tevfik R\u00fc\u015ft\u00fc Aras]]\n| office4        = [[Ministry of Agriculture and Village Affairs (Turkey)|Minister of Agriculture]]\n| term_start4    = August 31, 1924\n| term_end4      = October 21, 1924\n| primeminister4 = [[Ismet In\u00f6n\u00fc]]\n| predecessor4   = [[Zekai Apayd\u0131n]]\n| successor4     = [[Hasan Fehmi (Ata\u00e7)]]\n| office5        = Mayor and Governor of Izmir\n| term_start5    = 1922\n| term_end5      = 1924\n| birth_date     = 1883\n| birth_place    = [[Kos|Istank\u00f6y]], [[Ottoman Empire]]\n| death_date     = {{death date|1959|01|10}}\n| death_place    = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| nationality    = Turkish\n| profession     = Jurist\n| spouse         =\n| alma_mater     = [[Galatasaray High School]], [[Istanbul University]] Faculty of Law, [[University of Paris]]\n| religion       =\n| party          =\n| signature      = \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya imzas\u0131.png\n| signature_alt  =\n| website        =\n}}\n\n'''\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya''' (1883 &ndash; January 10, 1959) was a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] civil servant and politician, who served as government minister, Minister of Interior  and [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of Turkey|Minister of Foreign affairs]] in several governments. \n\n== Biography == \n[[File:\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya Bey.jpg|thumb|150px|left|\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya in the 1920s]]\nBorn in [[\u0130stank\u00f6y]] (Kos), part of [[the Dodecanese]] in the then [[Ottoman Empire]], he finished [[Galatasaray High School]] before he graduated from Law School in 1908. He did his graduate work in [[Paris]], [[France]]. He worked as inspector of treasury for the Empire.\n\nAt the start of [[World War I]], \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc was appointed the Director of Settlement of Tribes and Migrants. The Director of Settlement of Tribes and Migrants was mainly tasked with managing the Armenian deportations during the [[Armenian Genocide]]. In September 1915, he was transferred to [[Aleppo]], an important location along the deportation route into the Syrian desert.<ref name=dundar>{{cite book|last1=D\u00fcndar|first1=Fuat|title=Crime of numbers the role of statistics in the Armenian question (1878-1918)|date=2010|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, NJ|isbn=1412843413|pages=113\u20134|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JwUZ2HeAn8UC}}</ref>\n\nAs the Armenian Genocide was underway, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc was tasked to administrate the concentration camps of Armenian deportees located in Syria. In order to manage the large influx of Armenians into the area, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc started a policy that enforced a certain ratio of Armenians to be left untouched. However, once the Armenians exceeded this ratio, they were evacuated from their camps and subsequently massacred.<ref name=agos>{{cite news|last1=Polatel|first1=Mehmet|title=Social engineer: \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya|url=http://www.agos.com.tr/en/article/11045/social-engineer-sukru-kaya|agency=Agos|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> On 19 December 1915, \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc is noted to have said to German engineer Bastendorff the following:<ref name=agos />\n{{quote|The final solution is the termination of the Armenian race. Clashes that have continued between Armenians and Muslims all along have now reached their final stage. The weaker side will be destroyed.}}\n\nHe was then assigned to [[Iraq]] but he resigned and moved to [[\u0130zmir]] (also known as [[Smyrna]]).\n\nHe worked as a teacher in [[Buca]] Sultanisi (high school). After the [[Armistice of Mudros]], he worked for the [[Turkish national movement]]. Following the occupation of Istanbul by The Entente powers, he was arrested by the British administration and was exiled to [[British Malta|Malta]]. He escaped to the continent from Malta and subsequently went to [[Anatolia]] and joined the [[Turkish War of Independence]].\n\nIn September 1925 he was a member of the Reform Conucil for the Reform of the East ({{Lang-tr|\u015eark \u0130slahat Enc\u00fcmeni}})<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00dcng\u00f6r|first=U\u011fur \u00dcmit|date=2008-09-23|title=Geographies of Nationalism and Violence: Rethinking Young Turk \u2018Social Engineering\u2019|url=http://journals.openedition.org/ejts/2583|journal=European Journal of Turkish Studies. Social Sciences on Contemporary Turkey|language=en|issue=7|doi=10.4000/ejts.2583|issn=1773-0546}}</ref>  which prepared the the [[1925 Report for Reform in the East (Turkey)|Report for Reform in the East]] ({{Lang-tr|\u015eark \u0130slahat Raporu}}).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Goner|first=Ozlem|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=bv8nDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=sark+islahat+raporu+and+the+kurds+s%C3%BCkr%C3%BC+kaya&source=bl&ots=blWLemDPcN&sig=ACfU3U0np4xb_bdqhJ4a_zjAVksFrrfNJQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwix-rvWhPPoAhXIjKQKHT9OANIQ6AEwAXoECAsQMg#v=onepage&q=sark%20islahat%20raporu%20and%20the%20kurds%20s%C3%BCkr%C3%BC%20kaya&f=false|title=Turkish National Identity and Its Outsiders: Memories of State Violence in Dersim|date=14 June 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=|isbn=978-1-315-46296-7|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gunter|first=Michael M.|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=XjZ7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT195&lpg=PT195&dq=sark+islahat+raporu&source=bl&ots=yUOtVBARTq&sig=ACfU3U3HvofM8NM5rI_HeayKaaaKu6dGFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjXgMOpifPoAhVTycQBHR30DUEQ6AEwB3oECAsQNA#v=onepage&q=sark%20islahat%20raporu&f=false|title=Routledge Handbook on the Kurds|date=2018-08-06|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-23798-3|language=en}}</ref> In 1930 he was the author of the outlines of [[Turkification]] ({{Lang-tr|T\u00fcrkle\u015ftirme Genelgesi}}). Non-Turkish languages should be suppressed and non-Turkish names of locations changed to Turkish ones.<ref name=\":0\" />   \n\n\u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya served as Minister of Agriculture, Minister of Foreign Affairs and Interior Minister in several cabinets between 1924 and 1938.\n\nHe died on 10 January 1959, in [[Istanbul]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Who is who database - [http://www.kimkimdir.gen.tr/kimkimdir.php?id=624 ''Biography of \u015e\u00fckr\u00fc Kaya''] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\