{"title_page": "Know My Name (book)", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Know My Name: A Memoir\n| image         = Know My Name, A Memoir.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Chanel Miller]]\n| audio_read_by = Chanel Miller<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouseaudio.com/book/553663/know-my-name/ |title=Know My Name by Chanel Miller |website=[[Penguin Random House Audio]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| cover_artist  = Jason Ramirez and Nayon Cho<ref name=\"Copyright\">{{cite book|author=Chanel Miller|title=Know My Name: A Memoir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5UabDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT2|date=September 24, 2019|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-7352-2371-4|page=2}}</ref>\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| subject       = ''[[People v. Turner]]''\n| genre         = [[Memoir]]\n| publisher     = [[Viking Press]]\n| pub_date      = September 24, 2019\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages         = 368\n| awards        = \n| isbn          = 978-0-7352-2370-7\n| oclc          = 1115007919\n| dewey         = \n| congress      = \n}}\n'''''Know My Name: A Memoir''''' is a [[memoir]] by American author [[Chanel Miller]]. In it, Miller writes about being sexually assaulted in January 2015, as well as the aftermath and subsequent court case ''[[People v. Turner]]''.<ref name=\"Liu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/sep/25/know-my-name-by-chanel-miller-review| title=Know My Name by Chanel Miller review \u2013 memoir of a sexual assault| website=The Guardian| date=25 September 2019| access-date=2 October 2019| first=Rebecca| last=Liu}}</ref>\n\n==Research and writing process==\nIn September 2019, [[Chanel Miller]] revealed herself as being \"Emily Doe\" in the ''[[People v. Turner]]'' case and released her book with the title, ''Know My Name: A Memoir,'' on September 4, 2019.<ref name=mprnewschanel>{{citation|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2019/09/04/npr-victim-of-brock-turner-sexual-assault-reveals-her-identity|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Victim of Brock Turner sexual assault reveals her identity|first=Lynn|last=Neary|work=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]}}</ref><ref name=knowmynamecbs>{{Citation|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chanel-miller-reads-her-victim-impact-statement-brock-turner-stanford-assault-60-minutes-2019-09-04/|date=September 4, 2019|access-date=September 4, 2019|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS]]|title='Know My Name': Chanel Miller, Stanford sex assault victim formerly known as \"Emily Doe,\" reveals her name}}</ref><ref name=youdontknowmebbc>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-us-canada-49573589/stanford-sexual-assault-chanel-miller-reads-victim-impact-statement|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|title=Stanford sexual assault: Chanel Miller reads victim impact statement}}</ref> She first began work on the book in 2017.<ref name=cosmochanel>{{citation|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a28912320/emily-doe-chanel-miller-sexually-assault-stanford-swimmer-brock-turner-identity-book/|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Chanel Miller, the Woman Sexually Assaulted by Ex\u2013Stanford Swimmer Brock Turner, Reveals Her Identity|first=Shannon|last=Barbour|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]}}</ref><ref name=knowmyname /><ref name=swimchanel>{{citation|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/know-my-name-chanel-miller-brock-turners-victim-reveals-her-name-ahead-of-memoir/|access-date=September 5, 2019|work=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|title='Know My Name \u2013 Chanel Miller': Brock Turner\u2019s Victim Reveals Her Name Ahead Of Memoir|date=September 5, 2019|first=Craig|last=Lord}}</ref> The book was an attempt by Miller to [[Reappropriation|reappropriate]] her [[narrative identity]] and describe the trauma she went through, after being referred to in the press as \"unconscious intoxicated woman\".<ref name=chaneldeseret>{{citation|url=https://www.deseret.com/2019/9/4/20849761/survivor-in-stanford-sexual-assault-case-comes-forward-with-name-memoir|access-date=September 5, 2019|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=September 4, 2019|title=Survivor in Stanford sexual assault case comes forward with name, memoir|first=Valerie|last=Jones}}</ref><ref name=mprnewschanel /><ref name=chaneltelegraph>{{Citation|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/sex/victim-stanford-sex-attacker-brock-turner-bravely-waives-anonymity/|work=The Telegraph|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|title=Victim of Stanford sex attacker Brock Turner bravely waives her anonymity|first=Eleanor|last=Steafel}}</ref> The author discusses her experience of the assault and the trial, as well as how she has coped since then.<ref name=chaneldeseret /><ref name=ellechanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a28910784/chanel-miller-emily-doe-brock-turner-sexual-assault-case/|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Chanel Miller Comes Forward as 'Emily Doe' From the Brock Turner Sexual Assault Case|first=Madison|last=Feller}}</ref><ref name=guardianchanel>{{citation|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/sep/05/stanford-sexual-assault-survivor-identifies-herself-before-release-of-memoir|title=Stanford sexual assault survivor identifies herself before release of memoir}}</ref> Through research for the work, Miller perused court transcripts and testimony of individuals involved in the court proceedings\u2014materials she had been unable to view throughout the trial of Brock Turner itself.<ref name=sbschanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/you-don-t-know-me-chanel-miller-comes-forward-as-victim-in-brock-turner-sexual-assault-case|access-date=September 5, 2019|title='You don\u2019t know me': Chanel Miller comes forward as victim in Brock Turner sexual assault case|first=Lydia|last=Feng|date=September 5, 2019|work=SBS News}}</ref><ref name=bookseller>{{Citation|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/emily-doe-reveals-her-true-identity-ahead-memoir-brock-turner-assault-1078341|work=The Bookseller|title='Emily Doe' reveals true identity ahead of memoir on Brock Turner assault|first=Heloise|last=Wood}}</ref><ref name=knowmyname>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/books/chanel-miller-brock-turner-assault-stanford.html|work=New York Times|date=4 Sep 2019|title=You Know Emily Doe\u2019s Story. Now Learn Her Name.}}</ref>\n\n==Cover art==\nThe cover art for the book was inspired by ''[[kintsugi]]'', which is the Japanese art of repairing broken pottery with powdered gold, emphasizing the cracks rather than covering them up.<ref name=\"Feller\"/>\n\n==Publication and sales==\nThe book was initially published by [[Viking Press|Viking Books]], through efforts by the publisher's editor-in-chief Andrea Schulz.<ref name=mtvchanel>{{citation|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3138036/chanel-miller-know-my-name-memoir/|work=MTV.com|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|first=Ella|last=Ceron|title=Her statement to her rapist went viral - now Chanel Miller is speaking out as herself}}</ref><ref name=dailybeastchanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/chanel-miller-stanford-swimmer-brock-turners-victim-comes-forward-publicly-for-first-time|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 4, 2019|access-date=September 4, 2019|title=Brock Turner\u2019s Victim Reveals Her Identity|first=Audrey|last=McNamara}}</ref><ref name=irishtimeschanel>{{citation|work=[[Irish Times]]|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/know-my-name-stanford-sexual-assault-victim-reveals-identity-in-new-memoir-1.4009060|date=September 5, 2019|access-date=September 5, 2019|title=Know My Name: Stanford sexual assault victim reveals identity in new memoir}}</ref> Schulz took quick action after being contacted by Miller's [[literary agent]], Philippa Brophy.<ref name=irishtimeschanel /> Schulz worked to acquire the rights to the book because of Miller's writing skill and her compelling account.<ref name=sfgatechanel>{{Citation|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/chanel-miller-know-my-name-book-14412932.php|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|title='Emily Doe' in Brock Turner case steps forward, identifies herself as Chanel Miller|first=Katie|last=Dowd}}</ref><ref name=dailybeastchanel /><ref name=irishtimeschanel /> The same month as the book's publication, Miller was interviewed on [[CBS News]] program ''[[60 Minutes]]'', where she read from her original victim impact statement.<ref name=peoplechanel>{{citation|url=https://people.com/crime/woman-sexually-assaulted-by-stanford-swimmer-brock-turner-chanel-miller/|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|title=Woman Sexually Assaulted by Stanford Swimmer Reveals Her Identity|first=Greg|last=Hanlon}}</ref><ref name=yahoochanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/chanel-miller-survivor-center-brock-160127402.html|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|agency=Yahoo! Entertainment|title=Chanel Miller, Survivor at the Center of Brock Turner Case, Comes Forward|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=EJ|last=Dickson}}</ref><ref name=guardianchanel />\n\n''Know My Name'' debuted on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] at number five, and also made number 14 on the ''[[USA Today]]'' Best-Selling Books list.<ref name=bookpulse>{{citation|url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?detailStory=bestsellers-bookpulse-1032019|access-date=October 28, 2019|work=[[Library Journal]]|quote=Know My Name: A Memoir by Chanel Miller (Viking: Penguin) reclaims her story at No. 5 on the NYT Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers list and No. 14 on the USA Today Best-Selling Books list.|title=New Bestsellers, Oct. 3, 2019 - Book Pulse|first=Neal|last=Wyatt|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=nytbestseller>{{citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/10/13/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=October 28, 2019|date=October 13, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Oct 13. 2019|quote=New This Week - Know My Name - by Chanel Miller - Viking - A sexual assault victim reclaims her identity and challenges our culture and criminal justice system as they relate to this issue.}}</ref> The work additionally made the list of Best-Selling Books on ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name=wsjbest>{{citation|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-september-28-11570117918|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended September 28|access-date=October 28, 2019|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nRebecca Liu wrote that ''Know My Name'' was \"unapologetically large\", calling Miller's presence \"dazzling\" and undiminishable.<ref name=\"Liu\"/> Madison Feller of ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' magazine called it \"both an open wound and a salve, a quiet cry and the loudest scream\".<ref name=\"Feller\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/books/a29133859/chanel-miller-know-my-name-review-memoir/| first=Madison|last=Feller| date=24 September 2019| access-date=2 October 2019| website=Elle| title=We Knew Everything About the Worst Night of Her Life. Now, Chanel Miller Wants Us to Know Her Name}}</ref>\n\nU.S. Congresswoman [[Jackie Speier]], who coordinated the June 2016 movement in Congress to openly read the text of Miller's victim statement into the [[United States House of Representatives]],<ref name=speiercongress>{{Citation|url=https://www.congress.gov/crec/2016/06/15/modified/CREC-2016-06-15-pt1-PgH3905.htm|title=Words From a Sexual Assault Survivor to Her Attacker|work=[[Congressional Record]]|volume=162|issue=95|date=June 15, 2016|pages=H3905-H3909|publisher=From the Congressional Record Online through the Government Publishing Office|agency=[[United States House of Representatives]]|access-date=September 5, 2019|first=Jackie|last=Speier|authorlink=Jackie Speier}}</ref> called the book \"a powerful example of how we can overcome adversity\".<ref name=ktrk-tv>{{citation|url=https://abc13.com/brock-turners-sex-assault-victim-makes-her-name-public/5514799/|access-date=September 5, 2019|title=Brock Turner's sex assault victim makes her name public|date=September 5, 2019|first=Chris|last= Nguyen|work=[[KTRK-TV]]}}</ref> [[Stanford Law School|Stanford law professor]] [[Michele Dauber]] commented \"When people read her book, they will be impressed with her. They will be convinced that Judge Persky and Stanford University behaved very badly.\"<ref name=proudfoot>{{citation|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|work=Marie Claire UK|url=https://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/chanel-miller-667341|title=Brock Turner\u2019s anonymous sexual assault victim has identified herself|first=Jenny|last=Proudfoot}}</ref><ref name=standardchanel>{{citation|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/i-m-emily-doe-sex-assault-case-victim-reveals-identity-in-book-a4229806.html|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|first=Tristan|last=Kirk|title=\u2018I\u2019m Emily Doe\u2019: Sex assault case victim reveals identity in book|work=[[Evening Standard]]}}</ref> After Miller made the decision to go public with her real name, [[Stanford University]] released a statement: \"We applaud Ms. Miller's bravery in talking publicly about the ordeal she has experienced and the horrible act that she suffered on our campus. As a university, we are continuing our efforts to prevent and respond effectively to sexual violence, with the ultimate goal of eradicating it from our community.\"<ref name=ktrk-tv />\n\nThe book was named one of the top ten books of 2019 by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Best Books of 2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/entertainment/books/best-books-of-2019/ |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> It was nominated for Best Memoir & Autobiography at the 2019 [[Goodreads]] Choice Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/choiceawards/best-memoir-autobiography-books-2019|title=Best Memoir & Autobiography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Goodreads]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref> 2019 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] (Autobiography) winner for ''Know My Name''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Award Winners |url=https://www.bookcritics.org/2020/03/12/2020-awards/ |work=bookcritics.org |author=Beth Parker |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American memoirs]]\n[[Category:Viking Press books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = Know My Name: A Memoir\n| image         = Know My Name, A Memoir.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Chanel Miller]]\n| audio_read_by = Chanel Miller<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouseaudio.com/book/553663/know-my-name/ |title=Know My Name by Chanel Miller |website=[[Penguin Random House Audio]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| cover_artist  = Jason Ramirez and Nayon Cho<ref name=\"Copyright\">{{cite book|author=Chanel Miller|title=Know My Name: A Memoir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5UabDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT2|date=September 24, 2019|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-7352-2371-4|page=2}}</ref>\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| subject       = ''[[People v. Turner]]''\n| genre         = [[Memoir]]\n| publisher     = [[Viking Press]]\n| pub_date      = September 24, 2019\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages         = 368\n| awards        = \n| isbn          = 978-0-7352-2370-7\n| oclc          = 1115007919\n| dewey         = \n| congress      = \n}}\n'''''Know My Name: A Memoir''''' is a [[memoir]] by American author [[Chanel Miller]]. In it, Miller writes about being sexually assaulted in January 2015, as well as the aftermath and subsequent court case ''[[People v. Turner]]''.<ref name=\"Liu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/sep/25/know-my-name-by-chanel-miller-review| title=Know My Name by Chanel Miller review \u2013 memoir of a sexual assault| website=The Guardian| date=25 September 2019| access-date=2 October 2019| first=Rebecca| last=Liu}}</ref>\n\n==Research and writing process==\nIn September 2019, [[Chanel Miller]] revealed herself as being \"Emily Doe\" in the ''[[People v. Turner]]'' case and released her book with the title, ''Know My Name: A Memoir,'' on September 4, 2019.<ref name=mprnewschanel>{{citation|url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2019/09/04/npr-victim-of-brock-turner-sexual-assault-reveals-her-identity|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Victim of Brock Turner sexual assault reveals her identity|first=Lynn|last=Neary|work=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]}}</ref><ref name=knowmynamecbs>{{Citation|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chanel-miller-reads-her-victim-impact-statement-brock-turner-stanford-assault-60-minutes-2019-09-04/|date=September 4, 2019|access-date=September 4, 2019|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS]]|title='Know My Name': Chanel Miller, Stanford sex assault victim formerly known as \"Emily Doe,\" reveals her name}}</ref><ref name=youdontknowmebbc>{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-us-canada-49573589/stanford-sexual-assault-chanel-miller-reads-victim-impact-statement|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|title=Stanford sexual assault: Chanel Miller reads victim impact statement}}</ref> She first began work on the book in 2017.<ref name=cosmochanel>{{citation|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/politics/a28912320/emily-doe-chanel-miller-sexually-assault-stanford-swimmer-brock-turner-identity-book/|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Chanel Miller, the Woman Sexually Assaulted by Ex\u2013Stanford Swimmer Brock Turner, Reveals Her Identity|first=Shannon|last=Barbour|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]}}</ref><ref name=knowmyname /><ref name=swimchanel>{{citation|url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/know-my-name-chanel-miller-brock-turners-victim-reveals-her-name-ahead-of-memoir/|access-date=September 5, 2019|work=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|title='Know My Name \u2013 Chanel Miller': Brock Turner\u2019s Victim Reveals Her Name Ahead Of Memoir|date=September 5, 2019|first=Craig|last=Lord}}</ref> The book was an attempt by Miller to [[Reappropriation|reappropriate]] her [[narrative identity]] and describe the trauma she went through, after being referred to in the press as \"unconscious intoxicated woman\".<ref name=chaneldeseret>{{citation|url=https://www.deseret.com/2019/9/4/20849761/survivor-in-stanford-sexual-assault-case-comes-forward-with-name-memoir|access-date=September 5, 2019|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=September 4, 2019|title=Survivor in Stanford sexual assault case comes forward with name, memoir|first=Valerie|last=Jones}}</ref><ref name=mprnewschanel /><ref name=chaneltelegraph>{{Citation|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/sex/victim-stanford-sex-attacker-brock-turner-bravely-waives-anonymity/|work=The Telegraph|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|title=Victim of Stanford sex attacker Brock Turner bravely waives her anonymity|first=Eleanor|last=Steafel}}</ref> The author discusses her experience of the assault and the trial, as well as how she has coped since then.<ref name=chaneldeseret /><ref name=ellechanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/career-politics/a28910784/chanel-miller-emily-doe-brock-turner-sexual-assault-case/|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|title=Chanel Miller Comes Forward as 'Emily Doe' From the Brock Turner Sexual Assault Case|first=Madison|last=Feller}}</ref><ref name=guardianchanel>{{citation|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/sep/05/stanford-sexual-assault-survivor-identifies-herself-before-release-of-memoir|title=Stanford sexual assault survivor identifies herself before release of memoir}}</ref> Through research for the work, Miller perused court transcripts and testimony of individuals involved in the court proceedings\u2014materials she had been unable to view throughout the trial of Brock Turner itself.<ref name=sbschanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/you-don-t-know-me-chanel-miller-comes-forward-as-victim-in-brock-turner-sexual-assault-case|access-date=September 5, 2019|title='You don\u2019t know me': Chanel Miller comes forward as victim in Brock Turner sexual assault case|first=Lydia|last=Feng|date=September 5, 2019|work=SBS News}}</ref><ref name=bookseller>{{Citation|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/emily-doe-reveals-her-true-identity-ahead-memoir-brock-turner-assault-1078341|work=The Bookseller|title='Emily Doe' reveals true identity ahead of memoir on Brock Turner assault|first=Heloise|last=Wood}}</ref><ref name=knowmyname>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/books/chanel-miller-brock-turner-assault-stanford.html|work=New York Times|date=4 Sep 2019|title=You Know Emily Doe\u2019s Story. Now Learn Her Name.}}</ref>\n\n==Cover art==\nThe cover art for the book was inspired by ''[[kintsugi]]'', which is the Japanese art of repairing broken pottery with powdered gold, emphasizing the cracks rather than covering them up.<ref name=\"Feller\"/>\n\n==Publication and sales==\nThe book was initially published by [[Viking Press|Viking Books]], through efforts by the publisher's editor-in-chief Andrea Schulz.<ref name=mtvchanel>{{citation|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3138036/chanel-miller-know-my-name-memoir/|work=MTV.com|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|first=Ella|last=Ceron|title=Her statement to her rapist went viral - now Chanel Miller is speaking out as herself}}</ref><ref name=dailybeastchanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/chanel-miller-stanford-swimmer-brock-turners-victim-comes-forward-publicly-for-first-time|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=September 4, 2019|access-date=September 4, 2019|title=Brock Turner\u2019s Victim Reveals Her Identity|first=Audrey|last=McNamara}}</ref><ref name=irishtimeschanel>{{citation|work=[[Irish Times]]|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/know-my-name-stanford-sexual-assault-victim-reveals-identity-in-new-memoir-1.4009060|date=September 5, 2019|access-date=September 5, 2019|title=Know My Name: Stanford sexual assault victim reveals identity in new memoir}}</ref> Schulz took quick action after being contacted by Miller's [[literary agent]], Philippa Brophy.<ref name=irishtimeschanel /> Schulz worked to acquire the rights to the book because of Miller's writing skill and her compelling account.<ref name=sfgatechanel>{{Citation|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/chanel-miller-know-my-name-book-14412932.php|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|title='Emily Doe' in Brock Turner case steps forward, identifies herself as Chanel Miller|first=Katie|last=Dowd}}</ref><ref name=dailybeastchanel /><ref name=irishtimeschanel /> The same month as the book's publication, Miller was interviewed on [[CBS News]] program ''[[60 Minutes]]'', where she read from her original victim impact statement.<ref name=peoplechanel>{{citation|url=https://people.com/crime/woman-sexually-assaulted-by-stanford-swimmer-brock-turner-chanel-miller/|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|title=Woman Sexually Assaulted by Stanford Swimmer Reveals Her Identity|first=Greg|last=Hanlon}}</ref><ref name=yahoochanel>{{Citation|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/chanel-miller-survivor-center-brock-160127402.html|access-date=September 4, 2019|date=September 4, 2019|agency=Yahoo! Entertainment|title=Chanel Miller, Survivor at the Center of Brock Turner Case, Comes Forward|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=EJ|last=Dickson}}</ref><ref name=guardianchanel />\n\n''Know My Name'' debuted on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]] at number five, and also made number 14 on the ''[[USA Today]]'' Best-Selling Books list.<ref name=bookpulse>{{citation|url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?detailStory=bestsellers-bookpulse-1032019|access-date=October 28, 2019|work=[[Library Journal]]|quote=Know My Name: A Memoir by Chanel Miller (Viking: Penguin) reclaims her story at No. 5 on the NYT Hardcover Nonfiction Best Sellers list and No. 14 on the USA Today Best-Selling Books list.|title=New Bestsellers, Oct. 3, 2019 - Book Pulse|first=Neal|last=Wyatt|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=nytbestseller>{{citation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/10/13/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=October 28, 2019|date=October 13, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Oct 13. 2019|quote=New This Week - Know My Name - by Chanel Miller - Viking - A sexual assault victim reclaims her identity and challenges our culture and criminal justice system as they relate to this issue.}}</ref> The work additionally made the list of Best-Selling Books on ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name=wsjbest>{{citation|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-september-28-11570117918|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended September 28|access-date=October 28, 2019|date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nRebecca Liu wrote that ''Know My Name'' was \"unapologetically large\", calling Miller's presence \"dazzling\" and undiminishable.<ref name=\"Liu\"/> Madison Feller of ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]'' magazine called it \"both an open wound and a salve, a quiet cry and the loudest scream\".<ref name=\"Feller\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/books/a29133859/chanel-miller-know-my-name-review-memoir/| first=Madison|last=Feller| date=24 September 2019| access-date=2 October 2019| website=Elle| title=We Knew Everything About the Worst Night of Her Life. Now, Chanel Miller Wants Us to Know Her Name}}</ref>\n\nU.S. Congresswoman [[Jackie Speier]], who coordinated the June 2016 movement in Congress to openly read the text of Miller's victim statement into the [[United States House of Representatives]],<ref name=speiercongress>{{Citation|url=https://www.congress.gov/crec/2016/06/15/modified/CREC-2016-06-15-pt1-PgH3905.htm|title=Words From a Sexual Assault Survivor to Her Attacker|work=[[Congressional Record]]|volume=162|issue=95|date=June 15, 2016|pages=H3905-H3909|publisher=From the Congressional Record Online through the Government Publishing Office|agency=[[United States House of Representatives]]|access-date=September 5, 2019|first=Jackie|last=Speier|authorlink=Jackie Speier}}</ref> called the book, \"a powerful example of how we can overcome adversity\".<ref name=ktrk-tv>{{citation|url=https://abc13.com/brock-turners-sex-assault-victim-makes-her-name-public/5514799/|access-date=September 5, 2019|title=Brock Turner's sex assault victim makes her name public|date=September 5, 2019|first=Chris|last= Nguyen|work=[[KTRK-TV]]}}</ref> [[Stanford Law School|Stanford law professor]] [[Michele Dauber]] commented \"When people read her book, they will be impressed with her. They will be convinced that Judge Persky and Stanford University behaved very badly.\"<ref name=proudfoot>{{citation|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|work=Marie Claire UK|url=https://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/chanel-miller-667341|title=Brock Turner\u2019s anonymous sexual assault victim has identified herself|first=Jenny|last=Proudfoot}}</ref><ref name=standardchanel>{{citation|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/i-m-emily-doe-sex-assault-case-victim-reveals-identity-in-book-a4229806.html|access-date=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019|first=Tristan|last=Kirk|title=\u2018I\u2019m Emily Doe\u2019: Sex assault case victim reveals identity in book|work=[[Evening Standard]]}}</ref> After Miller made the decision to go public with her real name, [[Stanford University]] released a statement: \"We applaud Ms. Miller's bravery in talking publicly about the ordeal she has experienced and the horrible act that she suffered on our campus. As a university, we are continuing our efforts to prevent and respond effectively to sexual violence, with the ultimate goal of eradicating it from our community.\"<ref name=ktrk-tv />\n\nThe book was named one of the top ten books of 2019 by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Best Books of 2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2019/entertainment/books/best-books-of-2019/ |accessdate=November 26, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2019}}</ref> It was nominated for Best Memoir & Autobiography at the 2019 [[Goodreads]] Choice Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/choiceawards/best-memoir-autobiography-books-2019|title=Best Memoir & Autobiography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Goodreads]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref> 2019 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] (Autobiography) winner for ''Know My Name''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcing the 2019 Award Winners |url=https://www.bookcritics.org/2020/03/12/2020-awards/ |work=bookcritics.org |author=Beth Parker |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American memoirs]]\n[[Category:Viking Press books]]\n", "name_user": "Kbabej", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Know_My_Name_(book)"}
{"title_page": "Yazid II", "text_new": "{{about|the ninth Umayyad caliph|the 10th/11th-century ruler of Azerbaijan|Yazid II of Shirvan}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name          = Yazid II <br /> \u064a\u0632\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643\n| title         = [[List of Caliphs|Khal\u012bfah]] <br/> [[Amir al-Mu'minin]]\n| image         = [[File:Yazid II. Dinar.jpg|300px]]\n| caption       =  [[Gold dinar]] of Yazid II\n| succession    = 9th [[Caliph]] of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]\n| reign         = 9 February 720 \u2013 28 January 724\n| full name     = Ab\u016b Kh\u0101lid Yaz\u012bd ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n\n| predecessor   = [[Umar II]]\n| successor     = [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]]\n| dynasty       = [[Umayyad]]\n| father        = [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|\u02bfAbd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n]]\n| mother        = [[Atikah bint Yazid|\u02bf\u0100tika bint Yaz\u012bd]]\n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n*Umm al-\u1e24ajjaj bint Mu\u1e25ammad ibn Y\u016bsuf al-Thaqaf\u012byya\n*Su\u02bfd\u0101 bint \u02bfAbd All\u0101h ibn \u02bfAmr ibn \u02bfUthm\u0101n \n}}\n| issue         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Al-Walid II|Al-Wal\u012bd II]]\n*Al-Ghamr\n*Al-Nu\u02beman\n*\u02bfAbd al-Jabbar\n*Mu\u1e25ammad\n*Ya\u1e25y\u0101\n*Sulaym\u0101n\n*Al-H\u0101shim\n*Al-\u02bfAww\u0101m\n*\u02bfAbd All\u0101h\n*\u02bf\u0100\u02beisha (daughter)\n}}\n| birth_date    = {{circa|690/91}}\n| birth_place   = [[Damascus]], [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]]\n| death_date    = 26 January 724  (aged 34) (24 Sha'ban 105 AH)\n| death_place   = [[Irbid]], Syria\n| religion      = [[Islam]]\n}}\n'''Yazid bin Abd al-Malik''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0632\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643|Yaz\u012bd ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik}}; {{circa|690/91}} \u2014 28 January 724), also referred to as '''Yazid II''', was the ninth [[Umayyad]] [[caliph]], ruling from 9 February 720 until his death in 724.\n\n==Origins, early life and family==\nYazid was born in [[Damascus]], the center of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], {{circa|690/91}}.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} He was the son of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}) and his influential wife [[Atikah bint Yazid|Atika]], the daughter of Yazid II's namesake, Caliph [[Yazid I]] ({{reign|680|683}}).{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid II's pedigree united his father's [[Marwan I|Marwanid]] branch of the [[Umayyad dynasty]], in power since 684, and the [[Sufyanid]] branch of Yazid I and the latter's father [[Mu'awiya I]] ({{reign|661|680}}), founder of the Umayyad Caliphate.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} \n\nYazid did not possess military or administrative experience before his reign.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} He rarely left [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] except for a number of visits to the [[Hejaz]] (western [[Arabia]], home  of the Islamic holy cities [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]]),{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} including once for the annual [[Hajj]] pilgrimage sometime between 715 and 717.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=195}} He was possibly granted control of the region around [[Amman]] by Abd al-Malik.{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|pp=30, 32, 33}} \n\nYazid established marital ties to the family of the powerful viceroy of Iraq for his father and brother Caliph [[al-Walid I]] ({{reign|705|715}}), [[al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf]] (d. 714), marrying the latter's niece Umm al-Hajjaj, the daughter of [[Muhammad ibn Yusuf al-Thaqafi]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=89\u201390}} During the lifetime of al-Hajjaj, she gave birth to Yazid's sons al-Hajjaj, who died young, and [[al-Walid II]], who became caliph in 743.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}} Yazid was also married to Su'da bint Abd Allah ibn Amr, a great-granddaughter of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}), who mothered Yazid's son and daughter Abd Allah and A'isha, respectively.{{sfn|Ahmed|2010|p=123}} Yazid's other sons were al-Nu'man,{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=70}} Yahya, Muhammad, al-Ghamr, Sulayman, Abd al-Jabbar, Dawud, Abu Sulayman, al-Awwam and Hashim.{{sfn|Biesterfeldt|G\u00fcnther|2018|p=1031}} Yazid's ''[[kunya (Arabic)|kunya]]'' (patronmyic) was Abu Khalid and he was nicknamed ''al-Fata'' (the Youth).{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=193\u2013194}}\n\nAn anecdote told of Yazid is that his wife Su'da learning he was pining for an expensive slave girl, purchased this slave girl and presented her to Yazid as a gift. This woman's name was [[Hababah (slave)|Hababah]] and she predeceased Yazid.<ref>al-Tabari v. 24, p.&nbsp;196</ref> It is said that, while feasting with [[Hababah (slave)|Hababah]], Yazid threw a grape into her mouth, on which she choked and died in his arms. Yazid died the next week.<ref>{{Cite book| title = The Age of Faith| last = Durant| first = Will| work = [[The Story of Civilization]]| publisher = Simon and Schuster| year = 1950| isbn = | volume = 4| location = New York| pages = 195}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of desert palaces near Amman===\n[[File:Qasr al-Qastal 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|A building in the palatial complex of [[Al Qastal, Jordan|al-Qastal]] (pictured in 2018) built by Yazid]]\n\nYazid built the [[Desert castles|Umayyad desert palaces]] of [[Al Qastal, Jordan|al-Qastal]] and [[al-Muwaqqar]], both in the general vicinity of Amman. The palaces are conventionally held to have been built during his caliphate, though a number of archaeologists suggest Yazid began their construction before 720.{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|p=36}}\n\n==Reign==\n===Accession===\nBy dint of his descent, Yazid was a natural candidate for the succession to the caliphate.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} A noble Arab maternal lineage held political weight during this period in the Caliphate's history,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312, note 1}} and Yazid took pride in his maternal Sufyanid descent, viewing himself superior to his Marwanid brothers.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}} He was chosen by his paternal half-brother Caliph [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik|Sulayman]] ({{reign|715|717}}) as the second-in-line for the caliphate after their first cousin [[Umar II]], who ruled from 717 to 720.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid acceded at the age of 29 following the death of Umar II on 9 February 720.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=105}} For much of his reign, he resided in Damascus or his estates in [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (the military district of Jordan),{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} which was centered in [[Tiberias]] and roughly corresponded with the Byzantine province of [[Palaestina Secunda]].{{sfn|Cobb|2000|p=882}}\n\n===Suppression of Muhallabids===\n[[File:Dihram of Yazid II, 721-722.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Silver [[dirham]] of Yazid II, minted in 721/22]]\n\nShortly before or immediately after Yazid's accession, the veteran commander and disgraced governor of Iraq and the vast eastern province of [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]], [[Yazid ibn al-Muhallab]], escaped from the fortress of [[Aleppo]] where Umar II had him imprisoned.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=80, note 287}} During Sulayman's reign, Ibn al-Muhallab, an enemy of al-Hajjaj, had been responsible for the torture and deaths of members of al-Hajjaj's family, Yazid's in-laws, and feared retaliatory maltreatment when Yazid's accession became apparent.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} Yazid had long held suspicions, nurtured by al-Hajjaj, of Ibn al-Muhallab's and the [[Muhallabids|Muhallabid]] family's influence and ambitions in Iraq and the eastern Caliphate.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} \n\nEvading the pursuit of Umar's or Yazid's commanders, Ibn al-Muhallab made his way to [[Basra]], the center of his family and [[Azd|Azd Uman]] tribe.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} On Yazid's orders Basra's governor [[Adi ibn Artah al-Fazari|Adi ibn Artat al-Fazari]] arrested many of Ibn al-Muhallab's brothers and cousins before his arrival to the city.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=112}} Ibn Artat was unable to stop Ibn al-Muhallab's entry and the latter, with support from his Yamani tribal allies in the Basra garrison, besieged Ibn Artat in the city's citadel.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} The Qays\u2013Mudar factions of the garrison, though [[Qays\u2013Yaman rivalry|traditional rivals of the Yaman]] and unsympathetic to Ibn al-Muhallab, did not actively or effectively oppose him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Ibn al-Muhallab seized the citadel, captured the governor and established control over Basra.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Yazid pardoned him, but Ibn al-Muhallab continued his opposition, declaring a [[jihad|holy war]] (''jih\u0101d'') against the caliph and the Syrian troops who effectively served as the enforcers of Umayyad authority in Iraq.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Umar II had likely withdrawn most of the Syrians from [[Wasit]], their main Iraqi garrison, and Ibn al-Muhallab was able to capture the city with relative ease.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=313, 316}} Most of the pious [[Qur'an]] readers and the ''[[mawla|maw\u0101l\u012b]]'' (non-Arab Muslim converts) of Basra supported Ibn al-Muhallab's cause, with the exception of the prominent scholar [[al-Hasan al-Basri]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=314\u2013315}} The dependent districts of Basra, namely [[Ahwaz]], [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]] and [[Kerman]], joined the revolt, though not Khurasan, where Qays\u2013Mudar troops counterbalanced the pro-Muhallabid Yamani faction in the province's garrisons.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=315\u2013316}} \n\nIbn al-Muhallab advanced toward [[Kufa]], the other main garrison center of Iraq, where he attracted support across the tribal spectrum and among many of its noble Arab households.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=316\u2013317}} In the meantime, Yazid dispatched his kinsmen, the veteran commanders [[Maslama ibn Abd al-Malik]] and [[al-Abbas ibn al-Walid]], to suppress the revolt.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=127}} They killed Ibn al-Muhallab and routed his army near Kufa on 24 August 720.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=318}} Yazid ordered the executions of the roughly two hundred prisoners-of-war captured from Ibn al-Muhallab's camp, while Ibn al-Muhallab's son Mu'awiya ordered the execution of Ibn Artat and his thirty supporters incarcerated in Wasit.{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=140\u2013141}} Afterward, the Umayyad authorities pursued and killed many of the Muhallabids, including nine to fourteen boys who were sent to Yazid and executed by his order.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=318\u2013319}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=144\u2013146}}\n\n====Escalation of Qays\u2013Yaman factionalism====\n{{see also|Qays\u2013Yaman rivalry}}\n\nThe Muhallabid revolt's suppression marked the last of the great anti-Umayyad uprisings in Iraq.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=108}} The defeat of the Muhallabids and Yazid's successive appointments to the governorship of Iraq of Maslama\u2014who was shortly dismissed for not forwarding the provincial tax surplus to the caliph's treasury\u2014and Maslama's lieutenant [[Umar ibn Hubayra al-Fazari]] signaled a triumph for the Qays\u2013Mudar faction in the province and its eastern dependencies.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=319\u2013320}} According to the historian [[Julius Wellhausen]], \"the proscription of the whole of the prominent and powerful [Muhallabid] family, a measure hitherto unheard of in the history of the Umaiyids [sic], came like a declaration of war against the Yemen [faction] in general, and the corollary was that the government was degenerating into a Qaisite party-rule\".{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} Wellhausen blames the caliph for the escalation of factionalism and attributed the appointment of Ibn Hubayra to his own desire for revenge against the Muhallabids' Yamani backers.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} The Yamani-affiliated tribes of Khurasan viewed the events as a humiliation and during the [[Abbasid Revolution]] which toppled the Umayyads in 750 they adopted as one of their slogans \"revenge for the Banu Muhallab [Muhallabids]\".{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=76}} \n\nThe orientalist [[Henri Lammens]] considers Yazid's portrayal as \"a pro-Mudar and anti-Yaman extremist\" as \"unfair, as he actually tried to balance the conflicting groups, just as other Umayyad rulers did\".{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid did not champion the Qays over the [[Quda'a]], a major component of the Yaman confederation in Syria.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} Indeed, members of the Quda'a's principal tribe, the [[Banu Kalb]], had formed the core of the caliph's army during the suppression, pursuit and elimination of the Muhallabids.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} He appointed Yamani governors to the large provinces of [[Ifriqiya]] (North Africa west of Egypt) and the [[Upper Mesopotamia|Jazira]] (Upper Mesopotamia) and its dependent districts of [[Adharbayjan]] and [[Arminiya|Armenia]].{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}\n\n===Fiscal and military policies===\nThe expenses of enforcing Umayyad rule in Iraq and the expansionist war efforts along multiple fronts, including the enormous cost of the failed [[Siege of Constantinople (717\u2013718)|sieges of Constantinople in 717\u2013718]], had erased much of the monetary gains from the conquests of [[Transoxiana]], [[Arab Sind|Sind]] and the Iberian Peninsula under al-Walid I and caused a financial crisis in the Caliphate.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}} Among the solutions of Yazid's predecessor to the fiscal burden were the withdrawal of the Syrians from Iraq, a halt on conquests and near elimination of grants to Umayyad princes, as well as an unrealized goal to withdraw Arab troops altogether from Transoxiana, the Iberian Peninsula and [[Cilicia]].{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}} The most significant reforms of Umar II granted equality to the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in Khurasan, Sind, Ifriqiya and the Iberian Peninsula by abolishing the ''[[jizya]]'', the [[poll tax]] traditionally exacted on non-Muslim subjects but in practice extended to non-Arab Muslim converts, and instituting equal pay for ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in the ranks of the Caliphate's Arab-dominated armies.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=86}} According to Blankinship, the reforms favoring the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' may have been guided by Umar II's piety, but also a fiscal consideration: if equal treatment with the Arabs made the government popular with the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' it could translate into delegating an increased security role for the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in their native provinces and their enthusiastic defense of the Caliphate's frontiers, thereby reducing the expense of deploying and garrisoning Arab troops.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nYazid attempted to reverse, with limited success, the reforms of Umar II, which were opposed by the Arab militarist camp in the Caliphate and the Umayyad ruling family.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} During Umar II's rule the militarist camp led by Maslama may have accepted a temporary pause in activity to recover from the Constantinople debacle.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=86\u201387}} Under Yazid, Maslama and his proteges, including Ibn Hubayra, were restored or appointed to senior commands, Syrian garrisons were reintroduced to Iraq, the traditional annual raids against the Byzantines and the [[Arab\u2013Khazar wars|war with the Khazars]] were restarted, and the grants of estates or generous sums to Umayyad princes resumed.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} Although Yazid's policies were presumably meant to gain the backing of the ruling elite and restore the flow of war spoils, they proved insufficient to finance the Caliphate's troops, particularly as booty had become increasingly difficult to obtain by the Arab expeditionary forces.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}}\n\nTo fill the depleted coffers of the caliphal treasury Yazid turned to the fifth of provincial tax revenues officially owed to the caliph. Historically, the provinces neglected to forward the revenues if political conditions allowed and governors often pilfered such funds. To ensure the flow of revenues to the treasury, Yazid appointed governors based on the example set by al-Hajjaj, i.e. upright, meticulously loyal and ruthless in the collection of taxes.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} Unlike the era of al-Hajjaj, however, Yazid applied this principle for the first time to Ifriqiya, Khurasan, Sind and the Iberian Peninsula.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} A major aspect of his policy was the reinstatement of the ''jizya'' on the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'',{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} which alienated the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in the aforementioned provinces.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} \n\nIn Ifriqiya, the caliph's governor [[Yazid ibn Abi Muslim]], himself a ''mawl\u0101'' from Iraq and a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of al-Hajjaj, was assassinated by his [[Berbers|Berber]] guard in 720, shortly after his appointment, for attempting to reinstate the ''jizya''.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Many, if not most, Berbers had embraced Islam and commanded a strong position in the army unlike  ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in other parts of the Caliphate.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=87\u201388}} The Berbers reinstalled Ibn Abi Muslim's predecessor [[Ismail ibn Abd Allah ibn Abi al-Muhajir]] and notified Yazid, who approved the change.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=323}} The incident in Ifriqiya was a blow to the Caliphate's prestige in North Africa and served as a harbinger for the [[Berber Revolt]] in 740\u2013743.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} The reinstatement of the ''jizya'' in Khurasan in 721/22 by Ibn Hubayra's deputy [[Sa'id ibn Amr al-Harashi]] led to revolts and wars in the province that continued for twenty years and partly contributed to the Abbasid Revolution.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} In Egypt pay increases to the indigenous ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' sailors of the Muslim fleet were reversed.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}}\n\nAnti-Umayyad groups began to gain power among the disaffected. Al-Tabari records that [[Abbasids]] were promoting their cause in A.H. 102 (720-721 CE). They were already building a power base that they would later use to topple the Umayyads in 750 CE. \n\nThat same year Yazid's governor in [[Medina]], [['Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Dahhak ibn Qays al-Fihri|Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Dahhak]], incurred the caliph's displeasure because the governor was exerting undue pressure trying to force a woman to marry him. She appealed to Yazid who replaced Abd al-Rahman with Abd al-Walid ibn Abdallah.{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=180ff.}}\n\n===War against the Khazars===\nIn March 722 the Syrian army of Yazid's governor in Armenia and Adharbayjan, [[Mi'laq ibn Saffar al-Bahrani]], was routed by the [[Khazar Khaganate|Khazars]] in Armenia, south of the [[Caucasus]]. The defeat marked the culmination of the Caliphate's winter campaign against the Khazars and resulted in considerable Syrian losses.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=121\u2013122}} To avenge this defeat, Yazid II sent [[al-Jarrah ibn Abdallah]] at the head of a 25,000-strong army of Syrians, who pushed into the Caucasus homeland of the Khazars and took their capital of [[Balanjar]] on 22 August.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}} The main body of the highly mobile Khazars avoided the Muslims' pursuit and their presence compelled al-Jarrah to withdraw to Warthan south of the Caucasus and request reinforcements of from Yazid.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}} In 723 he led another raid north of Balanjar, but made no remarkable gains.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}}\n\n===Iconoclastic edict===\nAccording to Greek sources, including Patriarch [[John V of Jerusalem]] (d. 735), [[Theophanes the Confessor]] (d. 818) and Patriarch [[Nikephoros I of Constantinople]] (d. 828), Yazid issued an edict ordering the destruction of all [[icon]]s in Christian churches across the Caliphate under the influence a Jewish magician from Tiberias, variously called Beser or Tessarakontapechys, who promised Yazid a long life of fortune in return.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=27\u201333}} Syriac sources further note that Yazid entrusted Maslama to execute the order and that the edict influenced the Byzantine emperor [[Leo III the Isaurian|Leo III]] ({{reign|717|741}}) to enact his own iconoclastic policy in the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|p=37}} The Egypt-based Arabic historians [[Muhammad ibn Yusuf al-Kindi|al-Kindi]] (d. 961), Bishop [[Severus ibn al-Muqaffa]] (d. 987) and [[al-Maqrizi]] (d. 1442) also make note of the edict and describe its execution in Egypt.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=39\u201340}} The medieval historians cite different years for Yazid's edict, but the modern historian [[Alexander Vasiliev (historian)|Alexander Vasiliev]] holds that July 721, the date cited by Patriarch John V, is the most reliable.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|p=47}} The order was reversed by Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|724|743}}).{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=39\u201340}}\n\n===Death===\nYazid died in [[Irbid]] in the [[Balqa]] (e. g. [[Transjordan (region)|Transjordan]]) subdistrict of [[Jund Dimashq]] (military district of Damascus) on 26 [[Sha'ban]] 105 [[Anno Hegirae|AH]] (28 January 724 CE).{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=193\u2013194}} His son al-Walid or half-brother Hisham led his funeral prayers.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=194}} Yazid had intended to appoint al-Walid as his immediate successor, but was persuaded by Maslama to appoint Hisham instead, followed by al-Walid.{{sfn|Blankinship|1989|p=87, note 439}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Ahmed |first1=Asad Q. |title=The Religious Elite of the Early Islamic \u1e24ij\u0101z: Five Prosopographical Case Studies |date=2010 |publisher=University of Oxford Linacre College Unit for Prosopographical Research |location=Oxford |isbn=978-1-900934-13-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v1dwdBDDjcUC |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Bacharach |first=Jere L. |authorlink=Jere L. Bacharach | title=Marwanid Umayyad Building Activities: Speculations on Patronage |pages=27\u201344 |journal=Muqarnas: An Annual on the Visual Cultures of the Islamic World |year=1996 |volume=13 |jstor=1523250  |publisher=Brill |issn=2211-8993 |ref=harv |doi=10.1163/22118993-90000355}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Biesterfeldt |first1=Hinrich |last2=G\u00fcnther |first2=Sebastian |title=The Works of Ibn W\u0101\u1e0di\u1e25 al-Ya\u02bfq\u016bb\u012b (Volume 3): An English Translation |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-35621-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHxTDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=25 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Al-Urdunn: 2. History, (a) Up to 1250 |last=Cobb |first=P. M. |authorlink=Paul M. Cobb |volume=10 |page=882\u2013884}}\n*{{The First Dynasty of Islam|edition=Second}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=26 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates |edition=Second}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Yaz\u012bd (II) b. \u02bfAbd al-Malik |last1=Lammens |first1=H. |authorlink=Henri Lammens |last2=Blankinship |first2=Kh. Y. |authorlink2=Khalid Yahya Blankinship |volume=11 |page=311}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=24 |url={{Google Books|kIKGclA7YykC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vasiliev |first1=A. A.  |authorlink=Alexander Vasiliev (historian) |title=The Iconoclastic Edict of the Caliph Yazid II, A. D. 721 |journal=Dumbarton Oaks Papers |date=1956 |volume=9 |pages=23-47 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/1291091 |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Kingdom and its Fall}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Umayyad Dynasty]]||691||28 January 724}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Umar II]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = [[List of Caliphs|Caliph of Islam]]<br />[[Umayyad Caliph]]|years=9 February 720 \u2013 28 January 724}}\n{{S-aft|after  = [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik|Hisham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Umayyads}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yazid}}\n[[Category:690 births]]\n[[Category:724 deaths]]\n[[Category:8th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:8th-century Umayyad caliphs]]\n[[Category:History of Amman]]\n[[Category:Iconoclasm]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the ninth Umayyad caliph|the 10th/11th-century ruler of Azerbaijan|Yazid II of Shirvan}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name          = Yazid II <br /> \u064a\u0632\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643\n| title         = [[List of Caliphs|Khal\u012bfah]] <br/> [[Amir al-Mu'minin]]\n| image         = [[File:Yazid II. Dinar.jpg|300px]]\n| caption       =  [[Gold dinar]] of Yazid II\n| succession    = 9th [[Caliph]] of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]]\n| reign         = 9 February 720 \u2013 28 January 724\n| full name     = Ab\u016b Kh\u0101lid Yaz\u012bd ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n\n| predecessor   = [[Umar II]]\n| successor     = [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]]\n| dynasty       = [[Umayyad]]\n| father        = [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|\u02bfAbd al-Malik ibn Marw\u0101n]]\n| mother        = [[Atikah bint Yazid|\u02bf\u0100tika bint Yaz\u012bd]]\n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n*Umm al-\u1e24ajjaj bint Mu\u1e25ammad ibn Y\u016bsuf al-Thaqaf\u012byya\n*Su\u02bfd\u0101 bint \u02bfAbd All\u0101h ibn \u02bfAmr ibn \u02bfUthm\u0101n \n}}\n| issue         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Al-Walid II|Al-Wal\u012bd II]]\n*Al-Ghamr\n*Al-Nu\u02beman\n*\u02bfAbd al-Jabbar\n*Mu\u1e25ammad\n*Ya\u1e25y\u0101\n*Sulaym\u0101n\n*Al-H\u0101shim\n*Al-\u02bfAww\u0101m\n*\u02bfAbd All\u0101h\n*\u02bf\u0100\u02beisha (daughter)\n}}\n| birth_date    = {{circa|690/91}}\n| birth_place   = [[Damascus]], [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]]\n| death_date    = 26 January 724  (aged 34) (24 Sha'ban 105 AH)\n| death_place   = [[Irbid]], Syria\n| religion      = [[Islam]]\n}}\n'''Yazid bin Abd al-Malik''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0632\u064a\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643|Yaz\u012bd ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik}}; {{circa|690/91}} \u2014 28 January 724), also referred to as '''Yazid II''', was the ninth [[Umayyad]] [[caliph]], ruling from 9 February 720 until his death in 724.\n\n==Origins, early life and family==\nYazid was born in [[Damascus]], the center of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], {{circa|690/91}}.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} He was the son of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}) and his influential wife [[Atikah bint Yazid|Atika]], the daughter of Yazid II's namesake, Caliph [[Yazid I]] ({{reign|680|683}}).{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid II's pedigree united his father's [[Marwan I|Marwanid]] branch of the [[Umayyad dynasty]], in power since 684, and the [[Sufyanid]] branch of Yazid I and the latter's father [[Mu'awiya I]] ({{reign|661|680}}), founder of the Umayyad Caliphate.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} \n\nYazid did not possess military or administrative experience before his reign.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} He rarely left [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] except for a number of visits to the [[Hejaz]] (western [[Arabia]], home  of the Islamic holy cities [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]]),{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} including once for the annual [[Hajj]] pilgrimage sometime between 715 and 717.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=195}} He was possibly granted control of the region around [[Amman]] by Abd al-Malik.{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|pp=30, 32, 33}} \n\nYazid established marital ties to the family of the powerful viceroy of Iraq for his father and brother Caliph [[al-Walid I]] ({{reign|705|715}}), [[al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf]] (d. 714), marrying the latter's niece Umm al-Hajjaj, the daughter of [[Muhammad ibn Yusuf al-Thaqafi]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=89\u201390}} During the lifetime of al-Hajjaj, she gave birth to Yazid's sons al-Hajjaj, who died young, and [[al-Walid II]], who became caliph in 743.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}} Yazid was also married to Su'da bint Abd Allah ibn Amr, a great-granddaughter of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}), who mothered Yazid's son and daughter Abd Allah and A'isha, respectively.{{sfn|Ahmed|2010|p=123}} Yazid's other sons were al-Nu'man,{{sfn|Hillenbrand|1989|p=70}} Yahya, Muhammad, al-Ghamr, Sulayman, Abd al-Jabbar, Dawud, Abu Sulayman, al-Awwam and Hashim.{{sfn|Biesterfeldt|G\u00fcnther|2018|p=1031}} Yazid's ''[[kunya (Arabic)|kunya]]'' (patronmyic) was Abu Khalid and he was nicknamed ''al-Fata'' (the Youth).{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=193\u2013194}}\n\nAn anecdote told of Yazid is that his wife Su'da learning he was pining for an expensive slave girl, purchased this slave girl and presented her to Yazid as a gift. This woman's name was [[Hababah (slave)|Hababah]] and she predeceased Yazid.<ref>al-Tabari v. 24, p.&nbsp;196</ref> It is said that, while feasting with [[Hababah (slave)|Hababah]], Yazid threw a grape into her mouth, on which she choked and died in his arms. Yazid died the next week.<ref>{{Cite book| title = The Age of Faith| last = Durant| first = Will| work = [[The Story of Civilization]]| publisher = Simon and Schuster| year = 1950| isbn = | volume = 4| location = New York| pages = 195}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of desert palaces near Amman===\n[[File:Qasr al-Qastal 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|A building in the palatial complex of [[Al Qastal, Jordan|al-Qastal]] (pictured in 2018) built by Yazid]]\n\nYazid built the [[Desert castles|Umayyad desert palaces]] of [[Al Qastal, Jordan|al-Qastal]] and [[al-Muwaqqar]], both in the general vicinity of Amman. The palaces are conventionally held to have been built during his caliphate, though a number of archaeologists suggest Yazid began their construction before 720.{{sfn|Bacharach|1996|p=36}}\n\n==Reign==\n===Accession===\nBy dint of his descent, Yazid was a natural candidate for the succession to the caliphate.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} A noble Arab maternal lineage held political weight during this period in the Caliphate's history,{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312, note 1}} and Yazid took pride in his maternal Sufyanid descent, viewing himself superior to his Marwanid brothers.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=312}} He was chosen by his paternal half-brother Caliph [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik|Sulayman]] ({{reign|715|717}}) as the second-in-line for the caliphate after their first cousin [[Umar II]], who ruled from 717 to 720.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid acceded at the age of 29 following the death of Umar II on 9 February 720.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=105}} For much of his reign, he resided in Damascus or his estates in [[Jund al-Urdunn]] (the military district of Jordan),{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} which was centered in [[Tiberias]] and roughly corresponded with the Byzantine province of [[Palaestina Secunda]].{{sfn|Cobb|2000|p=882}}\n\n===Suppression of Muhallabids===\n[[File:Dihram of Yazid II, 721-722.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Silver [[dirham]] of Yazid II, minted in 721/22]]\n\nShortly before or immediately after Yazid's accession, the veteran commander and disgraced governor of Iraq and the vast eastern province of [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]], [[Yazid ibn al-Muhallab]], escaped from the fortress of [[Aleppo]] where Umar II had him imprisoned.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=80, note 287}} During Sulayman's reign, Ibn al-Muhallab, an enemy of al-Hajjaj, had been responsible for the torture and deaths of members of al-Hajjaj's family, Yazid's in-laws, and feared retaliatory maltreatment when Yazid's accession became apparent.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} Yazid had long held suspicions, nurtured by al-Hajjaj, of Ibn al-Muhallab's and the [[Muhallabids|Muhallabid]] family's influence and ambitions in Iraq and the eastern Caliphate.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} \n\nEvading the pursuit of Umar's or Yazid's commanders, Ibn al-Muhallab made his way to [[Basra]], the center of his family and [[Azd|Azd Uman]] tribe.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} On Yazid's orders Basra's governor [[Adi ibn Artah al-Fazari|Adi ibn Artat al-Fazari]] arrested many of Ibn al-Muhallab's brothers and cousins before his arrival to the city.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=112}} Ibn Artat was unable to stop Ibn al-Muhallab's entry and the latter, with support from his Yamani tribal allies in the Basra garrison, besieged Ibn Artat in the city's citadel.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=313}} The Qays\u2013Mudar factions of the garrison, though [[Qays\u2013Yaman rivalry|traditional rivals of the Yaman]] and unsympathetic to Ibn al-Muhallab, did not actively or effectively oppose him.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Ibn al-Muhallab seized the citadel, captured the governor and established control over Basra.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Yazid pardoned him, but Ibn al-Muhallab continued his opposition, declaring a [[jihad|holy war]] (''jih\u0101d'') against the caliph and the Syrian troops who effectively served as the enforcers of Umayyad authority in Iraq.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=314}} Umar II had likely withdrawn most of the Syrians from [[Wasit]], their main Iraqi garrison, and Ibn al-Muhallab was able to capture the city with relative ease.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=313, 316}} Most of the pious [[Qur'an]] readers and the ''[[mawla|maw\u0101l\u012b]]'' (non-Arab Muslim converts) of Basra supported Ibn al-Muhallab's cause, with the exception of the prominent scholar [[al-Hasan al-Basri]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=314\u2013315}} The dependent districts of Basra, namely [[Ahwaz]], [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]] and [[Kerman]], joined the revolt, though not Khurasan, where Qays\u2013Mudar troops counterbalanced the pro-Muhallabid Yamani faction in the province's garrisons.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=315\u2013316}} \n\nIbn al-Muhallab advanced toward [[Kufa]], the other main garrison center of Iraq, where he attracted support across the tribal spectrum and among many of its noble Arab households.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=316\u2013317}} In the meantime, Yazid dispatched his kinsmen, the veteran commanders [[Maslama ibn Abd al-Malik]] and [[al-Abbas ibn al-Walid]], to suppress the revolt.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=127}} They killed Ibn al-Muhallab and routed his army near Kufa on 24 August 720.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=318}} Yazid ordered the executions of the roughly two hundred prisoners-of-war captured from Ibn al-Muhallab's camp, while Ibn al-Muhallab's son Mu'awiya ordered the execution of Ibn Artat and his thirty supporters incarcerated in Wasit.{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=140\u2013141}} Afterward, the Umayyad authorities pursued and killed many of the Muhallabids, including nine to fourteen boys who were sent to Yazid and executed by his order.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=318\u2013319}}{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=144\u2013146}}\n\n====Escalation of Qays\u2013Yaman factionalism====\n{{see also|Qays\u2013Yaman rivalry}}\n\nThe Muhallabid revolt's suppression marked the last of the great anti-Umayyad uprisings in Iraq.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=108}} The defeat of the Muhallabids and Yazid's successive appointments to the governorship of Iraq of Maslama\u2014who was shortly dismissed for not forwarding the provincial tax surplus to the caliph's treasury\u2014and Maslama's lieutenant [[Umar ibn Hubayra al-Fazari]] signaled a triumph for the Qays\u2013Mudar faction in the province and its eastern dependencies.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=319\u2013320}} According to the historian [[Julius Wellhausen]], \"the proscription of the whole of the prominent and powerful [Muhallabid] family, a measure hitherto unheard of in the history of the Umaiyids [sic], came like a declaration of war against the Yemen [faction] in general, and the corollary was that the government was degenerating into a Qaisite party-rule\".{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} Wellhausen blames the caliph for the escalation of factionalism and attributed the appointment of Ibn Hubayra to his own desire for revenge against the Muhallabids' Yamani backers.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} The Yamani-affiliated tribes of Khurasan viewed the events as a humiliation and during the [[Abbasid Revolution]] which toppled the Umayyads in 750 they adopted as one of their slogans \"revenge for the Banu Muhallab [Muhallabids]\".{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=76}} \n\nThe orientalist [[Henri Lammens]] considers Yazid's portrayal as \"a pro-Mudar and anti-Yaman extremist\" as \"unfair, as he actually tried to balance the conflicting groups, just as other Umayyad rulers did\".{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Yazid did not champion the Qays over the [[Quda'a]], a major component of the Yaman confederation in Syria.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} Indeed, members of the Quda'a's principal tribe, the [[Banu Kalb]], had formed the core of the caliph's army during the suppression, pursuit and elimination of the Muhallabids.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=322}} He appointed Yamani governors to the large provinces of [[Ifriqiya]] (North Africa west of Egypt) and the [[Upper Mesopotamia|Jazira]] (Upper Mesopotamia) and its dependent districts of [[Adharbayjan]] and [[Arminiya|Armenia]].{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}\n\n===Fiscal and military policies===\nThe expenses of enforcing Umayyad rule in Iraq and the expansionist war efforts along multiple fronts, including the enormous cost of the failed [[Siege of Constantinople (717\u2013718)|sieges of Constantinople in 717\u2013718]], had erased much of the monetary gains from the conquests of [[Transoxiana]], [[Arab Sind|Sind]] and the Iberian Peninsula under al-Walid I and caused a financial crisis in the Caliphate.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}} Among the solutions of Yazid's predecessor to the fiscal burden were the withdrawal of the Syrians from Iraq, a halt on conquests and near elimination of grants to Umayyad princes, as well as an unrealized goal to withdraw Arab troops altogether from Transoxiana, the Iberian Peninsula and [[Cilicia]].{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}} The most significant reforms of Umar II granted equality to the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in Khurasan, Sind, Ifriqiya and the Iberian Peninsula by abolishing the ''[[jizya]]'', the [[poll tax]] traditionally exacted on non-Muslim subjects but in practice extended to non-Arab Muslim converts, and instituting equal pay for ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in the ranks of the Caliphate's Arab-dominated armies.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}}{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=86}} According to Blankinship, the reforms favoring the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' may have been guided by Umar II's piety, but also a fiscal consideration: if equal treatment with the Arabs made the government popular with the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' it could translate into delegating an increased security role for the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in their native provinces and their enthusiastic defense of the Caliphate's frontiers, thereby reducing the expense of deploying and garrisoning Arab troops.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=84\u201385}}\n\nYazid attempted to reverse, with limited success, the reforms of Umar II, which were opposed by the Arab militarist camp in the Caliphate and the Umayyad ruling family.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} During Umar II's rule the militarist camp led by Maslama may have accepted a temporary pause in activity to recover from the Constantinople debacle.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=86\u201387}} Under Yazid, Maslama and his proteges, including Ibn Hubayra, were restored or appointed to senior commands, Syrian garrisons were reintroduced to Iraq, the traditional annual raids against the Byzantines and the [[Arab\u2013Khazar wars|war with the Khazars]] were restarted, and the grants of estates or generous sums to Umayyad princes resumed.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} Although Yazid's policies were presumably meant to gain the backing of the ruling elite and restore the flow of war spoils, they proved insufficient to finance the the Caliphate's troops, particularly as booty had become increasingly difficult to obtain by the Arab expeditionary forces.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}}\n\nTo fill the depleted coffers of the caliphal treasury Yazid turned to the fifth of provincial tax revenues officially owed to the caliph. Historically, the provinces neglected to forward the revenues if political conditions allowed and governors often pilfered such funds. To ensure the flow of revenues to the treasury, Yazid appointed governors based on the example set by al-Hajjaj, i.e. upright, meticulously loyal and ruthless in the collection of taxes.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} Unlike the era of al-Hajjaj, however, Yazid applied this principle for the first time to Ifriqiya, Khurasan, Sind and the Iberian Peninsula.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} A major aspect of his policy was the reinstatement of the ''jizya'' on the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'',{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}} which alienated the ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in the aforementioned provinces.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} \n\nIn Ifriqiya, the caliph's governor [[Yazid ibn Abi Muslim]], himself a ''mawl\u0101'' from Iraq and a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of al-Hajjaj, was assassinated by his [[Berbers|Berber]] guard in 720, shortly after his appointment, for attempting to reinstate the ''jizya''.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} Many, if not most, Berbers had embraced Islam and commanded a strong position in the army unlike  ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' in other parts of the Caliphate.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=87\u201388}} The Berbers reinstalled Ibn Abi Muslim's predecessor [[Ismail ibn Abd Allah ibn Abi al-Muhajir]] and notified Yazid, who approved the change.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=323}} The incident in Ifriqiya was a blow to the Caliphate's prestige in North Africa and served as a harbinger for the [[Berber Revolt]] in 740\u2013743.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} The reinstatement of the ''jizya'' in Khurasan in 721/22 by Ibn Hubayra's deputy [[Sa'id ibn Amr al-Harashi]] led to revolts and wars in the province that continued for twenty years and partly contributed to the Abbasid Revolution.{{sfn|Lammens|Blankinship|2002|p=311}} In Egypt pay increases to the indigenous ''maw\u0101l\u012b'' sailors of the Muslim fleet were reversed.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=87}}\n\nAnti-Umayyad groups began to gain power among the disaffected. Al-Tabari records that [[Abbasids]] were promoting their cause in A.H. 102 (720-721 CE). They were already building a power base that they would later use to topple the Umayyads in 750 CE. \n\nThat same year Yazid's governor in [[Medina]], [['Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Dahhak ibn Qays al-Fihri|Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Dahhak]], incurred the caliph's displeasure because the governor was exerting undue pressure trying to force a woman to marry him. She appealed to Yazid who replaced Abd al-Rahman with Abd al-Walid ibn Abdallah.{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=180ff.}}\n\n===War against the Khazars===\nIn March 722 the Syrian army of Yazid's governor in Armenia and Adharbayjan, [[Mi'laq ibn Saffar al-Bahrani]], was routed by the [[Khazar Khaganate|Khazars]] in Armenia, south of the [[Caucasus]]. The defeat marked the culmination of the Caliphate's winter campaign against the Khazars and resulted in considerable Syrian losses.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|pp=121\u2013122}} To avenge this defeat, Yazid II sent [[al-Jarrah ibn Abdallah]] at the head of a 25,000-strong army of Syrians, who pushed into the Caucasus homeland of the Khazars and took their capital of [[Balanjar]] on 22 August.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}} The main body of the highly mobile Khazars avoided the Muslims' pursuit and their presence compelled al-Jarrah to withdraw to Warthan south of the Caucasus and request reinforcements of from Yazid.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}} In 723 he led another raid north of Balanjar, but made no remarkable gains.{{sfn|Blankinship|1994|p=122}}\n\n===Iconoclastic edict===\nAccording to Greek sources, including Patriarch [[John V of Jerusalem]] (d. 735), [[Theophanes the Confessor]] (d. 818) and Patriarch [[Nikephoros I of Constantinople]] (d. 828), Yazid issued an edict ordering the destruction of all [[icon]]s in Christian churches across the Caliphate under the influence a Jewish magician from Tiberias, variously called Beser or Tessarakontapechys, who promised Yazid a long life of fortune in return.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=27\u201333}} Syriac sources further note that Yazid entrusted Maslama to execute the order and that the edict influenced the Byzantine emperor [[Leo III the Isaurian|Leo III]] ({{reign|717|741}}) to enact his own iconoclastic policy in the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|p=37}} The Egypt-based Arabic historians [[Muhammad ibn Yusuf al-Kindi|al-Kindi]] (d. 961), Bishop [[Severus ibn al-Muqaffa]] (d. 987) and [[al-Maqrizi]] (d. 1442) also make note of the edict and describe its execution in Egypt.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=39\u201340}} The medieval historians cite different years for Yazid's edict, but the modern historian [[Alexander Vasiliev (historian)|Alexander Vasiliev]] holds that July 721, the date cited by Patriarch John V, is the most reliable.{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|p=47}} The order was reversed by Caliph [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|724|743}}).{{sfn|Vasiliev|1956|pp=39\u201340}}\n\n===Death===\nYazid died in [[Irbid]] in the [[Balqa]] (e. g. [[Transjordan (region)|Transjordan]]) subdistrict of [[Jund Dimashq]] (military district of Damascus) on 26 [[Sha'ban]] 105 [[Anno Hegirae|AH]] (28 January 724 CE).{{sfn|Powers|1989|pp=193\u2013194}} His son al-Walid or half-brother Hisham led his funeral prayers.{{sfn|Powers|1989|p=194}} Yazid had intended to appoint al-Walid as his immediate successor, but was persuaded by Maslama to appoint Hisham instead, followed by al-Walid.{{sfn|Blankinship|1989|p=87, note 439}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Ahmed |first1=Asad Q. |title=The Religious Elite of the Early Islamic \u1e24ij\u0101z: Five Prosopographical Case Studies |date=2010 |publisher=University of Oxford Linacre College Unit for Prosopographical Research |location=Oxford |isbn=978-1-900934-13-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v1dwdBDDjcUC |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Bacharach |first=Jere L. |authorlink=Jere L. Bacharach | title=Marwanid Umayyad Building Activities: Speculations on Patronage |pages=27\u201344 |journal=Muqarnas: An Annual on the Visual Cultures of the Islamic World |year=1996 |volume=13 |jstor=1523250  |publisher=Brill |issn=2211-8993 |ref=harv |doi=10.1163/22118993-90000355}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Biesterfeldt |first1=Hinrich |last2=G\u00fcnther |first2=Sebastian |title=The Works of Ibn W\u0101\u1e0di\u1e25 al-Ya\u02bfq\u016bb\u012b (Volume 3): An English Translation |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-35621-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHxTDwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=25 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Al-Urdunn: 2. History, (a) Up to 1250 |last=Cobb |first=P. M. |authorlink=Paul M. Cobb |volume=10 |page=882\u2013884}}\n*{{The First Dynasty of Islam|edition=Second}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=26 |url={{Google Books||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates |edition=Second}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Yaz\u012bd (II) b. \u02bfAbd al-Malik |last1=Lammens |first1=H. |authorlink=Henri Lammens |last2=Blankinship |first2=Kh. Y. |authorlink2=Khalid Yahya Blankinship |volume=11 |page=311}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=24 |url={{Google Books|kIKGclA7YykC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Vasiliev |first1=A. A.  |authorlink=Alexander Vasiliev (historian) |title=The Iconoclastic Edict of the Caliph Yazid II, A. D. 721 |journal=Dumbarton Oaks Papers |date=1956 |volume=9 |pages=23-47 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/1291091 |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Kingdom and its Fall}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Umayyad Dynasty]]||691||28 January 724}}\n{{S-bef|before = [[Umar II]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title  = [[List of Caliphs|Caliph of Islam]]<br />[[Umayyad Caliph]]|years=9 February 720 \u2013 28 January 724}}\n{{S-aft|after  = [[Hisham ibn Abd al-Malik|Hisham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Umayyads}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{