{"title_page": "The Lifecycle of Software Objects", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Lifecycle of Software Objects\n| title_orig    = The Lifecycle of Software Objects\n| translator    = \n| image         = The Lifecycle of Software Objects - bookcover.jpg\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = Hardcover edition \n| author        = [[Ted Chiang]]\n| cover_artist  = Christian Pearce\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Science Fiction]] [[novella]]\n| publisher     = [[Subterranean Press]]\n| release_date  = 2010\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages         = 150 pp (first edition, hardback)\n| isbn          = 978-1-59606-317-4\n| isbn_note     = (first edition, hardback)\n| dewey         =\n| congress      = \n| oclc          = 567188308\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\"'''The Lifecycle of Software Objects'''\" is a [[novella]] by American writer  [[Ted Chiang]] originally published in 2010 by [[Subterranean Press]].<ref>[http://www.subterraneanpress.com]   {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211140337/http://www.subterraneanpress.com/ |date=December 11, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThis is Chiang's first novella to be published originally in hardcover. As of December 22, 2010, both the [[first edition]] and trade edition have sold out, but the novella remains available in second printing from [[Subterranean Press]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chiang |first=Ted |url=http://www.subterraneanpress.com/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&Product_Code=chiang02&Category_Code=PRE&Product_Count=10 |title=The Lifecycle of Software Objects by Ted Chiang \u2014 Subterranean Press |publisher=Subterraneanpress.com |accessdate=2014-02-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307153646/http://www.subterraneanpress.com/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&Product_Code=chiang02&Category_Code=PRE&Product_Count=10 |archivedate=2012-03-07 }}</ref> The tale was later included in Chiang's second collection book ''[[Exhalation: Stories]]'' released in 2019.\n\nThe Subterreanean Press edition of the novella features ten internal paintings and cover art by [[Weta Workshop]] artist Christian Pearce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpearce.net/index.html=10 |title=Christian Pearce |publisher=Christian Pearce |date= |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> Each of the novella's ten chapters is preceded by a map designed by Jacob McMurray.\n\n==Story==\n\"The Lifecycle of Software Objects\" follows Ana Alvarado over a twenty-year period, during which she \"raises\" an [[artificial intelligence]] from being essentially a [[digital pet]] to a human-equivalent mind.\n\nAna, a former zoo trainer, is hired by a software developing company to assist in the training of digital creatures, named ''digients'' in the story, that are designed with a learning capacity similar to human children. Ana helps with the training and forms a close bond with Derek Brooks, a designer in charge of creating the visual appearance of the digients.\n\nBlue Gamma releases the digients in a virtual reality platform named Data Earth with big initial success, but after several years, the popularity of the digients diminishes and Blue Gamma closes. Several of the employees form a group to keep the digients active and learning; Ana keeps one named Jax and Derek keeps two named Marco and Polo. During these years, Derek develops unrequited feelings for Ana.\n\nAfter a few more years, the platform of Data Earth closes and merges with another digital platform named Real Space. Most of the games and software have already an equivalent there, but the digients don't because Blue Gamma closed before the launching of Real Space, which means they remain isolated at private servers running Data Earth. Ana, Derek and the other owners maintain a flow of learning activities for the digients, but they are unable to provide enough social interaction for them unless they can port them to Real Space, which prevents them to continue developing as social beings.\n\nAna receives an offer from another digient manufacturer, that wants her to train their digients to become personal assistants. She considers it an opportunity to convince them to invest on the digients she has been training, but the job offer has the downside that she would have to get her brain chemistry altered to reinforce her commitment to her work. On the other hand, the group receives an offer by a marketer of virtual sex dolls, that offers to pay for the port of the digients to Real Space in exchange of copies of the digients to train them as sex partners for their clients.\n\nMarco and Polo are intrigued by the offer, but Ana takes a strong position against it and instead prepares to accept the job offer. Upon learning that, Derek allows himself to be convinced by Marco to accept the offer of the sex doll company and sells them a copy of Marco, even if he knows that this will destroy any chance he has with Ana.\n\nAna finds out and has an awkward phone call with Derek. In the final scene, she is working on the education of Jax and meditates on the possibilities he will have at life, although she can't help feeling down because of the high price that was paid.\n\n==Awards==\n\u201cThe Lifecycle of Software Objects\u201d won the 2011 [[Locus Award]] for Best Novella<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/06/announcing-the-2011-locus-award-winners |title=Announcing the 2011 Locus Award Winners |publisher=Tor.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> and the [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Novella|Best Novella]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130306030242/http://subterraneanpress.com/magazine/fall_2010/fiction_the_lifecycle_of_software_objects_by_ted_chiang Online text edition of the novella at the Subterranean Press website]\n\n{{Hugo Award Best Novella}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lifecycle Of Software Objects}}\n[[Category:American novellas]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novel stubs]]\n[[Category:2010 American novels]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Novella winning works]]\n[[Category:Locus Award for Best Novella winning works]]\n[[Category:Works by Ted Chiang]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Lifecycle of Software Objects\n| title_orig    = The Lifecycle of Software Objects\n| translator    = \n| image         = The Lifecycle of Software Objects - bookcover.jpg\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = Hardcover edition \n| author        = [[Ted Chiang]]\n| cover_artist  = Christian Pearce\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Science Fiction]] [[novella]]\n| publisher     = [[Subterranean Press]]\n| release_date  = 2010\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages         = 150 pp (first edition, hardback)\n| isbn          = 978-1-59606-317-4\n| isbn_note     = (first edition, hardback)\n| dewey         =\n| congress      = \n| oclc          = 567188308\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\"'''The Lifecycle of Software Objects'''\" is a [[novella]] by American writer  [[Ted Chiang]] originally published in 2010 by [[Subterranean Press]].<ref>[http://www.subterraneanpress.com]   {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211140337/http://www.subterraneanpress.com/ |date=December 11, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThis is Chiang's first novella to be published originally in hardcover. As of December 22, 2010, both the [[first edition]] and trade edition have sold out, but the novella remains available in second printing from [[Subterranean Press]]'s website.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chiang |first=Ted |url=http://www.subterraneanpress.com/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&Product_Code=chiang02&Category_Code=PRE&Product_Count=10 |title=The Lifecycle of Software Objects by Ted Chiang \u2014 Subterranean Press |publisher=Subterraneanpress.com |accessdate=2014-02-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307153646/http://www.subterraneanpress.com/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&Product_Code=chiang02&Category_Code=PRE&Product_Count=10 |archivedate=2012-03-07 }}</ref> The tale was later included in Chiang's second collection book ''[[Exhalation: Stories]]'' released in 2019.\n\nThe Subterreanean Press edition of the novella features ten internal paintings and cover art by [[Weta Workshop]] artist Christian Pearce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpearce.net/index.html=10 |title=Christian Pearce |publisher=Christian Pearce |date= |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> Each of the novella's ten chapters is preceded by a map designed by Jacob McMurray.\n\n==Story==\n\"The Lifecycle of Software Objects\" follows Ana Alvarado over a twenty-year period, during which she \"raises\" an [[artificial intelligence]] from being essentially a [[digital pet]] to a human-equivalent mind.\n\nAna, a former zoo trainer, is hired by a software developing company to assist in the training of digital creatures, named ''digients'' in the story, that are designed with a learning capacity similar to human children. Ana helps with the training and forms a close bond with Derek Brooks, a designer in charge of creating the visual appearance of the digients.\n\nBlue Gamma releases the digients in a virtual reality platform named Data Earth with big initial success, but after several years, the popularity of the digients diminishes and Blue Gamma closes. Several of the employees form a group to keep the digients active and learning; Ana keeps one named Jax and Derek keeps two named Marco and Polo. During these years, Derek develops unrequited feelings for Ana.\n\nAfter a few more years, the platform of Data Earth closes and merges with another digital platform named Real Space. Most of the games and software have already an equivalent there, but the digients don't because Blue Gamma closed before the launching of Real Space, which means they remain isolated at private servers running Data Earth. Ana, Derek and the other owners maintain a flow of learning activities for the digients, but they are unable to provide enough social interaction for them unless they can port them to Real Space, which prevents them to continue developing as social beings.\n\nAna receives an offer from another digient manufacturer, that wants her to train their digients to become personal assistants. She considers it an opportunity to convince them to invest on the digients she has been training, but the job offer has the downside that she would have to get her brain chemistry altered to reinforce her commitment to her work. On the other hand, the group receives an offer by a marketer of virtual sex dolls, that offers to pay for the port of the digients to Real Space in exchange of copies of the digients to train them as sex partners for their clients.\n\nMarco and Polo are intrigued by the offer, but Ana takes a strong position against it and instead prepares to accept the job offer. Upon learning that, Derek allows himself to be convinced by Marco to accept the offer of the sex doll company and sells them a copy of Marco, even if he knows that this will destroy any chance he has with Ana.\n\nAna finds out and cuts all ties with Derek. In the final scene, she is working on the education of Jax and meditates on the possibilities he will have at life, although she can't help feeling down because of the high price that was paid.\n\n==Awards==\n\u201cThe Lifecycle of Software Objects\u201d won the 2011 [[Locus Award]] for Best Novella<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/06/announcing-the-2011-locus-award-winners |title=Announcing the 2011 Locus Award Winners |publisher=Tor.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2014-02-16}}</ref> and the [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Novella|Best Novella]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130306030242/http://subterraneanpress.com/magazine/fall_2010/fiction_the_lifecycle_of_software_objects_by_ted_chiang Online text edition of the novella at the Subterranean Press website]\n\n{{Hugo Award Best Novella}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lifecycle Of Software Objects}}\n[[Category:American novellas]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novel stubs]]\n[[Category:2010 American novels]]\n[[Category:Hugo Award for Best Novella winning works]]\n[[Category:Locus Award for Best Novella winning works]]\n[[Category:Works by Ted Chiang]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American novels]]\n", "name_user": "Modefier", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStory:fixed description of plot after reading book", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lifecycle_of_Software_Objects"}
{"title_page": "Maktoum bin Mohammed Al Maktoum", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| image                = Sheikh Maktoum.jpg\n| caption              = Sheikh Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum in October 2011\n| title                = Deputy ruler of Dubai<br />[[Sheikh]]\n| house                = [[House of Al-Falasi|Al Falasi]]\n| full name            = Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1983|11|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place          = [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] \n| spouse                 = Maryam bint Butti Al Maktoum (m. 2019)\n| father               = [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]]\n| mother               = [[Hind bint Maktoum bin Juma Al Maktoum]]\n| religion             = [[Islam]]\n}}\n{{Infobox royal styles\n|royal name = Deputy Ruler of Dubai\n|image     = [[File:Coat of arms of Dubai.svg|50px]]\n|dipstyle  = [[His Highness]]\n|offstyle  = Your Highness\n}}\n\n[[Sheikh]] '''Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0645 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0622\u0644 \u0645\u0643\u062a\u0648\u0645}}; born 24 November 1983) is the deputy ruler of [[Dubai]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Basit|first=Abdul|title=Best performing firms honoured|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticle.asp?xfile=data/business/2010/November/business_November4.xml&section=business&col=|accessdate=23 November 2010|newspaper=[[Khaleej Times]]|date=1 November 2010}}</ref> and the Chairman of [[Dubai Media Incorporated]]. He was named as the deputy ruler of Dubai in February 2008 when his elder brother Hamdan was made crown prince.<ref name=wikil>{{cite web|title=Dubai Designates Crown Prince and Deputy Ruler|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/08DUBAI57_a.html|work=Wikileaks|accessdate=15 April 2016|date=12 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMaktoum was born in 24 November 1983 in Dubai .<ref name=wikil/> He is the third son of Dubai's ruler, Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]]. His mother is Sheikha [[Hind bint Maktoum bin Juma Al Maktoum]]. He completed his high school at Rashid Private School, Dubai, and graduated from the [[American University in Dubai]]<ref name=\"wikil\"/> with a bachelor's degree in Business Administration in 2005. He attended numerous training courses in the [[Dubai School of Government]], as well as [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Sheikh Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum named Dubai Deputy Ruler|url=http://www.uaeinteract.com/docs/Sheikh_Maktoum_bin_Mohammed_bin_Rashid_Al_Maktoum_named_Dubai_Deputy_Ruler/28433.htm|accessdate=4 June 2013|newspaper=[[Khaleej Times]]|date=2 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nSheikh Maktoum chairs the Board of Directors of Dubai Media Incorporated and serves as the Chairman of Dubai Technology and Media Free Zone Authority (TECOM Investments). Sheikh Maktoum has accompanied the President of the [[United Arab Emirates]], Sheikh [[Khalifa bin Zayed Al Nahyan]], to numerous conferences, summits and official visits. He has also accompanied Sheikh Mohammed to several Gulf, Arab and international political and economic conferences.\n\nIn 6 June 2019, he married Maryam Bint Butti Al Maktoum in a royal wedding at the [[Dubai World Trade Center]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-celebrates-hamdan-maktoum-ahmad-weddings-1.64367858|title=UAE celebrates Hamdan, Maktoum, Ahmad weddings\n|newspaper=Gulf News|date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Sheikh Maktoum bin Mohammed Al Maktoum'''\n|2= 2. [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum|Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]]\n|3= 3. [[Hind bint Maktoum bin Juma Al Maktoum|Sheikha Hind bint Maktoum Al Maktoum]]\n|4= 4. [[Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum|Sheikh Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum]] \n|5= 5. Sheikha Latifa bint Hamdan Al Nahyan  \n|6= 6. Sheikh Maktoum bin Juma Al Maktoum\n|7= 7. Sheikha Shaikha bint Saeed Al Maktoum\n|8= 8. [[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum|Sheikh Saeed bin Maktoum Al Maktoum]] (= 14)\n|9= 9. Sheikha Hessa bint Al Murr\n|10= 10. Sheikh Hamdan bin Zayed Al Nahyan\n|11= 11. Sheikha Shamsa bint Obaid bin Mejren\n|12= 12. Sheikh Juma bin Maktoum Al Maktoum\n|14= 14. [[Saeed bin Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum|Sheikh Saeed bin Maktoum Al Maktoum]] (= 8)\n|16= 16. [[Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum|Sheikh Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum]] (=24, =28)\n|18= 18. Sheikh Al Murr\n|20= 20. [[Zayed bin Khalifa Al Nahyan|Sheikh Zayed bin Khalifa Al Nahyan]]\n|22= 22. Sheikh Obaid bin Mejren\n|24= 24. [[Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum|Sheikh Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum]] (=16, =28)\n|28= 28. [[Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum|Sheikh Maktoum bin Hasher Al Maktoum]] (=16, =24)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maktoum Bin Mohammed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Maktoum family]]\n[[Category:Emirati princes]]\n[[Category:American University in Dubai alumni]]\n[[Category:Dubai School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Dubai]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| image                = Sheikh Maktoum.jpg\n| caption              = Sheikh Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum in October 2011\n| title                = Deputy ruler of Dubai<br />[[Sheikh]]\n| house                = [[House of Al-Falasi|Al Falasi]]\n| full name            = Maktoum bin Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum\n| birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|1983|11|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place          = [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] \n| spouse                 = Maryam bint Butti Al Maktoum (m. 2019)\n| father               = [[Mohammed bin Rashid Al Ma